WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:04.770
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:24.020 --> 00:00:26.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: My name is Steve
Winick and we're here at the Library

00:00:26.130 --> 00:00:30.850
of Congress with Billy McComiskey
and his friend Myron Bretholz

00:00:30.850 --> 00:00:32.950
and his son Sean McComiskey.

00:00:32.950 --> 00:00:35.800
And we're here to talk about
Billy's career in music.

00:00:35.800 --> 00:00:39.970
And it's on an occasion that's
sort of a dual occasion.

00:00:39.970 --> 00:00:42.640
Number one, we're celebrating
the 40th anniversary

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:45.760
of the American Folklife Center
here at the Library of Congress.

00:00:45.760 --> 00:00:47.750
And Billy was one of the
performers who played

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:52.860
at the party celebrating our
creation back in February of 1976.

00:00:52.860 --> 00:00:55.130
So we're very happy to have
Billy here for that reason.

00:00:55.130 --> 00:00:58.850
And the second reason is--
this hasn't been announced yet

00:00:58.850 --> 00:01:01.960
but by the time this video
is available it will be--

00:01:01.960 --> 00:01:05.960
Billy is a recipient this
year of the National Endowment

00:01:05.960 --> 00:01:08.670
for the Arts National
Heritage Fellowship Award.

00:01:08.670 --> 00:01:13.910
And we're really happy to have
Billy here to sort of continue

00:01:13.910 --> 00:01:17.350
to document his life and
his career as a musician.

00:01:17.350 --> 00:01:21.040
And of course we're very happy also
to have Myron who's been active

00:01:21.040 --> 00:01:24.390
in Irish music for all
these years alongside Billy.

00:01:24.390 --> 00:01:28.400
And Sean, because one of the
reasons for having this concert was

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:32.180
to show how the tradition had
continued to develop over 40 years

00:01:32.180 --> 00:01:35.320
and we thought there was
no better symbol of that

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:37.440
than to have Billy here
with some of his children

00:01:37.440 --> 00:01:39.180
who also play Irish music.

00:01:39.180 --> 00:01:41.230
So, welcome to all three of you.

00:01:41.230 --> 00:01:42.530
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Thank you.

00:01:42.530 --> 00:01:43.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Thank you, Steve.

00:01:43.830 --> 00:01:45.130
Pleasure to be here.

00:01:45.130 --> 00:01:46.430
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And
I guess we'll start

00:01:46.430 --> 00:01:47.730
with some general questions
for Billy.

00:01:47.730 --> 00:01:50.890
I know your music career
started in your original hometown

00:01:50.890 --> 00:01:52.940
which was Brooklyn, New York.

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:57.970
So, talk a little about
Brooklyn and that scene.

00:01:57.970 --> 00:02:03.520 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: It-- We started
kind of right at the beginning,

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:12.310
my grandfather emigrated out
from Ireland from Nenagh--

00:02:12.310 --> 00:02:14.550
near Nenagh, let's put it that way.

00:02:14.550 --> 00:02:17.340
Actually, he was actually
from Newport in Tipperary

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:24.740 position:56%
and his wife was from Castleconnell,
which was in County Limerick.

00:02:24.740 --> 00:02:29.580
And so, their daughter
Mae McComiskey,

00:02:29.580 --> 00:02:31.300
that's-- that would be my mom.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:34.550
So she was actually
the first to the--

00:02:34.550 --> 00:02:38.360
of the Brooklyn-- of
our Brooklyn family.

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:39.660
She was the first daughter.

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:42.900
She had two brothers, one
older and one younger.

00:02:42.900 --> 00:02:50.000
And they were all crazy mad in
love with Irish traditional music

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.620
and it had an awful lot to do--
Nora-- Nora was just a great mother

00:02:54.620 --> 00:03:00.580
but it was my grandfather
was Andrew Caplis

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:02.920
from Newport in County Tipperary.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:05.000
And he was a lovely fiddle player.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.340
The great Larry Redican from Dublin
came to visit my grandfather.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:17.410 position:56%
As soon as he landed, as he landed
in New York, he found my grandfather

00:03:17.410 --> 00:03:21.760
and he just wanted to meet him and
talk a little bit about the music.

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:23.640
So it was kind of like that.

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:25.440
But it was-- We grew
up in a row house,

00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:29.150
I don't know how my
grandmother did at first.

00:03:29.150 --> 00:03:32.910
They were right in the depths
of the depression somehow.

00:03:32.910 --> 00:03:34.610
And they bought a house right

00:03:34.610 --> 00:03:39.040
in the neighborhood called
Windsor Terrace in Brooklyn.

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:42.120 position:56%
And my mother was just-- They were--

00:03:42.120 --> 00:03:48.080
She was just so close and just
loved her parents so much.

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:50.450
We ended up living
exactly right next door

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:52.460
to them, which is no easy feat.

00:03:52.460 --> 00:03:55.450
Brooklyn is a-- Brooklyn
is a tough town.

00:03:55.450 --> 00:03:57.160
She met-- she met my father--

00:03:57.160 --> 00:03:59.180
She met my father on
the Catskill Mountains.

00:03:59.180 --> 00:04:07.210
Her brother had a-- he
had a-- I'm slipping.

00:04:07.210 --> 00:04:08.530
You'll have to edit
that a little bit.

00:04:08.530 --> 00:04:11.570
A boarding house, in...a
boarding house called the Overlook

00:04:11.570 --> 00:04:12.870
in the Catskill Mountains.

00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:16.610
And my father had come
out from Northern Ireland.

00:04:16.610 --> 00:04:23.010
My father was an Irish Catholic
from Northern Ireland and he chose

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:28.000
to defend the crown during
the Second World War.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.480
He had a good talk with his
father and his, and they agreed

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:36.850 position:56%
that what was going on in Northern
Ireland, what the British were doing

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:38.600
to the Irish Catholics, the natives

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:41.390
of Ireland just wasn't--
it wasn't right.

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:43.590
But it was nowhere near
as bad as what was going

00:04:43.590 --> 00:04:46.280
on with the-- in Nazi Germany.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:49.510
So somehow or another, my
father actually became a pilot

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:52.890
for the Queen's Royal Air Force.

00:04:52.890 --> 00:04:59.960 position:56%
And he came out to Oklahoma to train
and he made a pact with himself

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:05.920 position:56%
that if he survived the war, he
would make his way back to Oklahoma.

00:05:05.920 --> 00:05:10.060
Or may-- I mean, maybe,
maybe just America.

00:05:10.060 --> 00:05:13.050
But he kind of, well, I'd really
like to get back to Oklahoma.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:16.990
When he got one look at it,
all of these land that was here

00:05:16.990 --> 00:05:20.830
and all you had to do is work
for it and you could have--

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:22.350
you could do anything you wanted.

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.930
It was what I loved when he would
talk about it when he first came

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:29.830
out here because this as a-- You
know, as a member of the old world,

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:33.380
you know, Northern Ireland,
it just wasn't the case.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:34.680
So he did, he came out.

00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:37.550
And he only made it-- He only
made it as far as Brooklyn

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:43.110
and he was staying at his aunt's
house and there was a burned

00:05:43.110 --> 00:05:46.740
out house down the
street from her house

00:05:46.740 --> 00:05:50.370
and he just couldn't
stand it and he bought it.

00:05:50.370 --> 00:05:52.900
So, it was in Brooklyn
that he decided--

00:05:52.900 --> 00:05:55.940
There was a couple there
on the street that said,

00:05:55.940 --> 00:05:58.140
could you bring us
up, we want to go--

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:00.490
We're going to stay in the boarding
house in the Catskill Mountains.

00:06:00.490 --> 00:06:02.440
Could you drive us up there?

00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:05.410
And he did, he went with
his best friend Pat Thompson

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:09.910
and Pat McComiskey hopped
in their '39 Chevy and drove

00:06:09.910 --> 00:06:11.420
up to the Catskill Mountains.

00:06:11.420 --> 00:06:15.490
And there was Matt
Caplis and he says, you--

00:06:15.490 --> 00:06:18.560
you two fellows should
stay over tonight

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:23.260
because there's a great
box player in town.

00:06:23.260 --> 00:06:26.180
And there was a bunch of women
playing badminton out in the lawn.

00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:29.160
And he says, and you have your
pick of the Catskills right there.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.460
You can have anyone.

00:06:30.460 --> 00:06:32.260 position:56%
And my father said, I like that one.

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:34.720
And this guy says, oh,
no, no, no, not that one.

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:39.400
So that's my mother
that my father picked.

00:06:39.400 --> 00:06:43.660
And his best friend, Pat Thompson
picked Kathleen Thompson, his wife.

00:06:43.660 --> 00:06:45.260
And they all kind of
stayed in Brooklyn.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:46.760
So there was this lovely
little community.

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:52.970
The box player that they went out
to hear that night was Joe Derrane

00:06:52.970 --> 00:06:59.160
who it-- he has been
such an inspiration.

00:06:59.160 --> 00:07:01.780
I listened to Joe's
music at the house.

00:07:01.780 --> 00:07:03.370
My mother had all of Joe's records.

00:07:03.370 --> 00:07:06.010
My Uncle Matt played the accordion.

00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:09.960 position:56%
He couldn't play like Joe Derrane
and he just-- he adored Joe Derrane.

00:07:09.960 --> 00:07:14.960
And so it's amazing, these
crazy little connections.

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:17.020
There was always-- So there
was always great music there

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:18.320
in Brooklyn.

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:19.830
My grandma-- And my
grandfather passed away.

00:07:19.830 --> 00:07:21.690
I never got to meet my grandfather.

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:26.190
But my grandmother and my mother
would take me up to 39th Street

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:31.700
and 5th Avenue to the Rainbow
Café on a Sunday and we would go

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:34.220
down to the back room
in the basement.

00:07:34.220 --> 00:07:37.650
And Paddy Sullivan, the Kerry
fiddler would be down there.

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:41.070
And he'd all-- And as soon as I
came in and it was 25 cents to get

00:07:41.070 --> 00:07:48.400
in to the Irish music club
and he would come up to us

00:07:48.400 --> 00:07:52.980
and he would say, Mrs.
Caplis, you don't have to pay.

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.680
It was 25 cents and that was a
lot of money for my grandmother.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:08:00.810
And he would bring us in and
we would get to just listen

00:08:00.810 --> 00:08:02.770
to the great musicians
that were living in

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:05.210
and around Brooklyn in those days.

00:08:05.210 --> 00:08:08.600
And awful lot of-- Mostly fiddle
players and flute players.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:11.310
It was just a really--
It was a lovely thing.

00:08:11.310 --> 00:08:15.370
Sometimes we'd save the money
for the bus and we'd walk in.

00:08:15.370 --> 00:08:16.730
When my grandmother was younger,

00:08:16.730 --> 00:08:19.140
we'd walk around Green-Wood
cemetery.

00:08:19.140 --> 00:08:21.300
So that's kind of how-- That's kind

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:24.500
of how Brooklyn was, I
guess in those times.

00:08:24.500 --> 00:08:28.600
My grandmother would not
let my grandfather go

00:08:28.600 --> 00:08:31.770
out to play in the Irish bars.

00:08:31.770 --> 00:08:36.550
During the depression, she would
not let that happen because here

00:08:36.550 --> 00:08:40.630
in Washington now with the
Dubliner or the Irish times

00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.150
in the four province, all these
beautiful Irish restaurants.

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:45.440
That was not the case in Brooklyn

00:08:45.440 --> 00:08:48.090
when my grandfather
was hanging out there.

00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:52.050
It was like you kind of had-- You
kind of had to know how to fight.

00:08:52.050 --> 00:08:54.810
And you kind of had
to know how to run.

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:59.030
And it was just kind of how
Brooklyn was and so that--

00:08:59.030 --> 00:09:01.850
No, it was a kind of a-- It was a--

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:04.440
There wasn't a whole lot to do
with Irish music at the time.

00:09:04.440 --> 00:09:07.470
You know, we're talking
about very modest people.

00:09:07.470 --> 00:09:14.050 position:56%
We were, you know, we were the
Latino speaking people of their day.

00:09:14.050 --> 00:09:17.860
I don't know how, I don't know is
that the right way to phrase that.

00:09:17.860 --> 00:09:20.910
But we were kind of-- We were
the downtrodden, you know,

00:09:20.910 --> 00:09:26.660
just kind of coming out of
this whole traumatic experience

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:28.960
with colonialism, you
know, and all that,

00:09:28.960 --> 00:09:33.780
just trying to figure their
way through the war --

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:35.300
for independence over in Ireland.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:40.700
So it's a pretty-- It was
pretty hard for that generation

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:44.550
of players-- generation of people
that were coming out in those days.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:49.890
You could see how relieved
they were to get to America.

00:09:49.890 --> 00:09:51.630
Lovely, quiet people.

00:09:51.630 --> 00:09:53.280
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So how
about when you were growing

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:54.850
up a few years later was--

00:09:54.850 --> 00:09:58.010
the music, had it taken off a
little bit more in Brooklyn?

00:09:58.010 --> 00:09:59.930
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: I
didn't realize it at the time

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:02.120
but the music was actually
on the verge of extinction.

00:10:02.120 --> 00:10:08.070
It was-- There was very,
very little of it left.

00:10:08.070 --> 00:10:12.420
My Uncle Matt and my Uncle
Andy were on a mission.

00:10:12.420 --> 00:10:18.150
They went and found the bars
in the Catskill Mountains

00:10:18.150 --> 00:10:21.750
that would host the great
musicians of the time.

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.260
My uncle-- There would be fellows--

00:10:23.260 --> 00:10:27.180 position:56%
song and dance kind of guys that
would playing in these guys' places.

00:10:27.180 --> 00:10:31.170
And my Uncle Matt would be
determined to get the likes

00:10:31.170 --> 00:10:34.910
of maybe Paddy Killoran,
the great sligo player.

00:10:34.910 --> 00:10:40.090
Maybe get him a gig or just
when he-- somehow or another,

00:10:40.090 --> 00:10:44.700
he was able to get Joe Cooley to
come up to my godfather's bar.

00:10:44.700 --> 00:10:48.190
Again, and I would-- I might have
been like 11 or 12 years old.

00:10:48.190 --> 00:10:52.270
So when you would go and nobody
was paying these people to do this,

00:10:52.270 --> 00:10:56.080
they would go because-- They would
go because Joe Cooley was there.

00:10:56.080 --> 00:11:00.220
Bobby Gardiner, the great Clare
box player from Lisdoonvarna,

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:02.170
after he won the All-Ireland, he--

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:05.730
He ended up in the Catskills
because he wanted to--

00:11:05.730 --> 00:11:07.080
he wanted to hear Joe Cooley.

00:11:07.080 --> 00:11:09.600
So it's funny how it, how
it kind of-- and kind of--

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:12.090
it was this inside kind of thing.

00:11:12.090 --> 00:11:15.260
It was like a-- it was
before the internet

00:11:15.260 --> 00:11:17.800
but there was somehow they
were able to communicate

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:20.630
to Boston players,
the New York players.

00:11:20.630 --> 00:11:23.790
So that was kind of it:
Boston, New York, maybe Chicago.

00:11:23.790 --> 00:11:26.030
In these little modest
Irish communities,

00:11:26.030 --> 00:11:30.750
there would be these
unbelievably talented players.

00:11:30.750 --> 00:11:35.600
I was stunned and mortified to
learn that the great Joe Heaney,

00:11:35.600 --> 00:11:38.800
the great sean nós singer,
actually lived in Bay Ridge.

00:11:38.800 --> 00:11:41.030
It wasn't even 10 minutes
from my house.

00:11:41.030 --> 00:11:43.410
But we just didn't know.

00:11:43.410 --> 00:11:45.130
We didn't know.

00:11:45.130 --> 00:11:48.850
It wasn't until the National
Council for the Traditional Arts

00:11:48.850 --> 00:11:51.790
that we realized that we're
in the presence of genius.

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:55.720
It was an amazing-- It was an
amazing thing that happened.

00:11:55.720 --> 00:11:57.180
A lot-- people like Larry Redican,

00:11:57.180 --> 00:11:59.540
Larry Redican actually
would have gotten

00:11:59.540 --> 00:12:01.670
to play on the Ed Sullivan Show.

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:04.270
He would have played
for the McNiff dancers.

00:12:04.270 --> 00:12:07.020
Maybe it was Jerry-- I think
he played with Jerry Wallace,

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:10.700
the pianist from Northern Ireland.

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:12.000
And this would-- That
would be about--

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:13.430
that would be a really great gig.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:14.770 position:56%
He wouldn't get any money from that.

00:12:14.770 --> 00:12:18.300
There was no money in playing
Irish traditional music.

00:12:18.300 --> 00:12:20.090
And there were just a few old men

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:23.790
that were just incredibly
good, you know.

00:12:23.790 --> 00:12:27.180 position:56%
And it was kind of-- the funny thing
was it was the same in Ireland.

00:12:27.180 --> 00:12:28.800
We would get over there.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:33.970
When I finally had the money, when
I had my little job in the Bank

00:12:33.970 --> 00:12:38.110
of New York, I managed to come up
with enough money for my air fare.

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:43.240
And all I had to do was get over
there and in between my relatives

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.660
who also love the music, the whole,

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:49.540
the Limerick players
and people, family.

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:53.560
And then the people that just loved
the music, so all I had to do is

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:57.070
to come up with the air fare and
I can get to stay for three weeks.

00:12:57.070 --> 00:13:00.810
And again, my Uncle Matt, he'd be a
couple of steps ahead of me trying

00:13:00.810 --> 00:13:05.060 position:56%
to figure out, well, maybe we can
go to Feakle tonight, maybe a couple

00:13:05.060 --> 00:13:06.360
of the old fellows or may--

00:13:06.360 --> 00:13:08.080
You know, maybe we can
find some of these guys.

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:13.610
Maybe Matthew Ryan will be in town
until maybe we can work this out.

00:13:13.610 --> 00:13:20.150
So this was say 1969-1970, and
for where I was in, I just--

00:13:20.150 --> 00:13:21.860
well, to me, it's just
like this little secret,

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:25.090
this beautiful little jewel.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:32.020
And I was too young to
realize it was almost vanished.

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:34.120
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Well, so
at some point before this,

00:13:34.120 --> 00:13:38.050
you actually started to play
and you started to play,

00:13:38.050 --> 00:13:39.990
you've been mentioning the box.

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:43.920
And of course that's typically
the button accordion--

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:45.220
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: That's right.

00:13:45.220 --> 00:13:46.520
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Typically
BC tune like yours.

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:47.820
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah.

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:50.050
Maybe not-- I guess that the tuning
kind of came later but, yeah,

00:13:50.050 --> 00:13:55.940 position:56%
we would be like I like it here, you
know, hey, I like that squeezebox.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:13:57.860
But the Irish never really
called it a squeezebox.

00:13:57.860 --> 00:14:04.120 position:56%
It would be a box or a melodeon, you
know, is another lovely expression.

00:14:04.120 --> 00:14:09.820
My cousin John Sweeney
really admired my Uncle Matt.

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:11.660
So he went in the--
He was in the navy.

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:15.150
He was a-- His mother passed away,
so he had to fend for himself.

00:14:15.150 --> 00:14:20.720
He went into the navy and he
went to Germany and he decided

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:22.020
to bring back an accordion.

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:25.250 position:56%
And just completely out of the blue,

00:14:25.250 --> 00:14:27.780
he bought what's called
Hohner blackdot,

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:34.270
which happens to be a BC
semitone button accordion.

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:38.130
And it's an interesting thing that
was-- that they, an Englishman,

00:14:38.130 --> 00:14:39.430
of course, I can't
think it was back--

00:14:39.430 --> 00:14:43.640
back in around 1910 discovered
that if you take two old scales,

00:14:43.640 --> 00:14:46.090
two major scales, two
diatonic scales,

00:14:46.090 --> 00:14:48.990
if they are a half a
step apart, you more

00:14:48.990 --> 00:14:50.830
or less have the full
circle of fifths.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:54.850
It doesn't make for a great
harmony playing instrument

00:14:54.850 --> 00:15:00.830 position:56%
but it was just ideal for the
lovely way that the Irish tradition.

00:15:00.830 --> 00:15:05.520
And Irish music is kind
of like pre-G clef.

00:15:05.520 --> 00:15:07.280
It's pre-chromatic.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:09.180
It's a diatonic kind of music.

00:15:09.180 --> 00:15:10.990
So when they figured
out what if it takes--

00:15:10.990 --> 00:15:13.370
It's kind of like what
the Cajun fellows play.

00:15:13.370 --> 00:15:15.710
And it's exactly the same
except there's two rows

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:18.760
and one will be a half step
apart from the other one.

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:22.720
Or up in Quebec, it was a
little single row accordion.

00:15:22.720 --> 00:15:24.770
So you get that lovely pulse.

00:15:24.770 --> 00:15:29.760
But when it's a semitone like that,
it's a little bit more capable.

00:15:29.760 --> 00:15:31.060
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:15:31.060 --> 00:15:32.800
Well, it helps you play in
more keys so you can play

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:35.170
with other people among
other things.

00:15:35.170 --> 00:15:38.560
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Well,
again, like yeah, it-- what I--

00:15:38.560 --> 00:15:41.600
Irish music is we don't
really know--

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:44.580
We don't really know how old it is.

00:15:44.580 --> 00:15:46.640
My friend, Jerry O'Sullivan
made a couple of--

00:15:46.640 --> 00:15:50.920
He's a great piper up in New
York, scholar, and he did a couple

00:15:50.920 --> 00:15:55.680
of recordings that he just
called O'Sullivan Meets O'Farrel.

00:15:55.680 --> 00:16:00.470
So the O'Farrel collection
was like the early 1700s.

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:03.830 position:56%
O Carolan's music is mixed in there.

00:16:03.830 --> 00:16:06.720
I guess that the amazing thing
about this-- And we would--

00:16:06.720 --> 00:16:08.910 position:56%
Patrick Street, Patrick, what is it?

00:16:08.910 --> 00:16:11.110
Something, so-- What's
the name of the record?

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:12.410
Fisher's--

00:16:12.410 --> 00:16:13.710
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz:
Oh, Fisher Street,

00:16:13.710 --> 00:16:15.010
that I mentioned today, right ?

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:16.310
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, did
a whole bunch of tunes from--

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:17.610
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Yeah, right.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:18.910
That's right.

00:16:18.910 --> 00:16:20.210
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: They
