00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:48.450
I don't know, I'm not an
ethnomusicologist or a folklorist.

00:16:48.450 --> 00:16:53.920
But it goes back there and it
exists in these beautiful modes

00:16:53.920 --> 00:17:00.300
that the pipers were--
are able to interpret

00:17:00.300 --> 00:17:03.340 position:56%
and it's just a-- it's-- it goes up.

00:17:03.340 --> 00:17:07.300
It goes up like a do, re, mi, so
these whole steps and half steps.

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:10.290
And the little modes that
existed around there.

00:17:10.290 --> 00:17:13.750
So, the one that saw the
pipers play these tunes.

00:17:13.750 --> 00:17:18.230
And so there's little blind
spots in the pipes that kind

00:17:18.230 --> 00:17:21.600
of identified the music
and it gives it--

00:17:21.600 --> 00:17:24.810
It makes it sound the way it does,
just like the little blind spots,

00:17:24.810 --> 00:17:28.370
the open strings on the
fiddle and stuff like that.

00:17:28.370 --> 00:17:32.290
So this is what the people
that were composing this music.

00:17:32.290 --> 00:17:35.070
I don't think we even
regard it as composing.

00:17:35.070 --> 00:17:38.790
We kind of-- we were talking
about making up a tune, you know,

00:17:38.790 --> 00:17:42.720
you kind of-- not really say
compose, you know, that's too fancy

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:45.970
for Irish music because
we're just regarded

00:17:45.970 --> 00:17:48.360
as a folk, as a people's music.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:50.750
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, one
thing that you tend to mention

00:17:50.750 --> 00:17:55.250 position:56%
