name is where that person was from.

00:17:55.250 --> 00:17:58.290
So let's talk about the
regions a little bit and how

00:17:58.290 --> 00:18:01.460
that influenced the music or
in your experience anyway.

00:18:01.460 --> 00:18:04.450
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: I'd be
kind of identified as a--

00:18:04.450 --> 00:18:10.990
and more loosely defined, as an
east Galway style accordion player.

00:18:10.990 --> 00:18:15.620
And the place, the reason that
would get a little dicey is Irish

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:23.250
accordion as I understand it came
into being, it started to exist in

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:28.240
and of itself someplace around
maybe 1950, the instrument--

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:29.700
that Paolo Soprani built--

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:32.550
well there was this black
dot Hohner accordion.

00:18:32.550 --> 00:18:33.850
But it wasn't complete.

00:18:33.850 --> 00:18:37.430
They hadn't quite figured
out how to make--

00:18:37.430 --> 00:18:39.860
Help the left hand to
accompany these tunes.

00:18:39.860 --> 00:18:43.200
So Paolo Soprani took
this idea from Hohner.

00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:48.290
Paolo Soprani from Castelfidardo,
pre-- and I guess beforehand,

00:18:48.290 --> 00:18:50.110
before and maybe even-- I'm not--

00:18:50.110 --> 00:18:52.200
I don't know about
during but definitely

00:18:52.200 --> 00:18:55.970
after World War II Paolo Soprani
was-- when Paolo Soprani went--

00:18:55.970 --> 00:18:59.510
from Castelfidardo was
considered like a national hero

00:18:59.510 --> 00:19:01.780
because he was a-- one of
these people that were able

00:19:01.780 --> 00:19:05.420
to get his countrymen employed.

00:19:05.420 --> 00:19:09.390
You know, we were talking
about the Chinese fiddle maker

00:19:09.390 --> 00:19:13.910
and it's kind of-- This is--
It's a beautiful craft, you know,

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:16.570
being able to just come

00:19:16.570 --> 00:19:23.760
up with these little simple
inexpensive little bits of things

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:30.290
and put them together so that these
lovely regular common people can

00:19:30.290 --> 00:19:34.870
make this beautifully--
beautiful, beautiful music.

00:19:34.870 --> 00:19:37.200
It's just a lovely gift.

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:44.780 position:56%
So, I don't know, I-- So, somehow in
the course of that and around 1950,

00:19:44.780 --> 00:19:49.540
this Irish style accordion--

00:19:49.540 --> 00:19:52.370
this Italian accordion
just became adapted--

00:19:52.370 --> 00:19:54.770
adopted by the Irish people.

00:19:54.770 --> 00:19:56.540
And there'd be a couple
of different semitone.

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:57.840
There's two.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:02.200 position:56%
Basically there's a BC and a C sharp
D. Joe Cooley would have played a C

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:03.500
sharp D.

00:20:03.500 --> 00:20:08.760
So he would be from
Peterswell in east Galway.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.100
Paddy O'Brien, this is where
it gets a little dicey.

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:14.660
Paddy O'Brien is from
Nenagh in County Tipperary.

00:20:14.660 --> 00:20:19.920
So it would be-- It'll be
like more of a-- It would be--

00:20:19.920 --> 00:20:24.210
If you are cycling from
Nenagh up into Galway,

00:20:24.210 --> 00:20:25.710
it would take you a little while.

00:20:25.710 --> 00:20:27.300
But this is kind of
what happened there.

00:20:27.300 --> 00:20:31.320
When they talk about-- So when they
talk about this east Galway style,

00:20:31.320 --> 00:20:34.530
it's not particularly
accordion music.

00:20:34.530 --> 00:20:39.980
It's the music that
existed in east Galway

00:20:39.980 --> 00:20:41.950
when the fiddle players would play.

00:20:41.950 --> 00:20:46.720
The great Paddy Fahey, that's still
alive, a very prolific composer,

00:20:46.720 --> 00:20:52.060 position:56%
would be writing these absolutely
stunning beautiful, beautiful tunes.

00:20:52.060 --> 00:20:54.660
There-- and sometimes there would
be-- and it would be like an--

00:20:54.660 --> 00:20:58.630
if you take the scale, maybe
a Mixolydian scale or a kind

00:20:58.630 --> 00:21:03.050
of combine a major scale with
this modal one and get a--

00:21:03.050 --> 00:21:05.180
all this beautiful stuff
going on with the fiddle.

00:21:05.180 --> 00:21:09.360
And the flute players
ended up having to resort

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:11.920
to chromatic flutes, which
is so, you know, the--

00:21:11.920 --> 00:21:16.340
all right, the old Irish players
would have the six hole diatonic

00:21:16.340 --> 00:21:17.640
flute, the transverse flute,

00:21:17.640 --> 00:21:21.040
and all of a sudden it
became borderline chromatic.

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:22.760
It is like a really
interesting thing to happen.

00:21:22.760 --> 00:21:24.680
And the accordion players
picked up on it.

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:27.280
So it would have been
maybe Joe Cooley would be--

00:21:27.280 --> 00:21:30.750
that this is the person that
everybody immediately thinks

00:21:30.750 --> 00:21:32.320
of with East Galway music.

00:21:32.320 --> 00:21:35.630
And Kevin Keegan, who
was a BC player,

00:21:35.630 --> 00:21:40.380
Kevin Keegan adored the playing
of Paddy O'Brien from Nenagh.

00:21:40.380 --> 00:21:46.570 position:56%
And Paddy O'Brien from Nenagh is
the man that kind of showed the way.

00:21:46.570 --> 00:21:52.240
He started creating a
technique for the BC accordion.

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:57.910
That Joe Cooley was
able to bring that--

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:02.720
bring the accordion a
step closer to what--

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:06.410
to the essence of the music so that
pipers and fiddlers would want to--

00:22:06.410 --> 00:22:08.430
They wanted to play with Joe.

00:22:08.430 --> 00:22:15.680
And then Paddy took that and the
technique grew because of that.

00:22:15.680 --> 00:22:21.580
Kevin Keegan would never play
in front of Paddy O'Brien.

00:22:21.580 --> 00:22:23.540
He just wouldn't, he just wouldn't.

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:27.810
But he was able to
be around Joe Cooley

00:22:27.810 --> 00:22:30.440
without being totally
intimidated by him.

00:22:30.440 --> 00:22:34.410
And then shortly after that-- So
that's the ground works up there

00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:41.510
and then people like Raymond
Roland from the town of Loughrea

00:22:41.510 --> 00:22:44.770
where Paddy Fahey would have--

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:48.010
would have met up with the great
Paddy Carty, the flute player.

00:22:48.010 --> 00:22:51.830
Loughrea was just one of
these great towns and-- but--

00:22:51.830 --> 00:22:55.600
So, Raymond Roland would be there
and then he ended up in London

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:57.850
and this whole thing
started in London.

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:01.380
The great Raymond Roland
quartet was there.

00:23:01.380 --> 00:23:04.360
Liam Farrell -- It's
funny now my-- our--

00:23:04.360 --> 00:23:12.150
my daughter-in-law is married to
the grand-niece of Liam Farrell.

00:23:12.150 --> 00:23:13.650
She was Lisa Farrell.

00:23:13.650 --> 00:23:17.350
So there's all these really
beautiful musical collection--

00:23:17.350 --> 00:23:18.650
connections.

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:26.610
So then from Raymond Roland came
these mighty, mighty players.

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:36.880 position:56%
Sean McGlynn from-- right from the
town of Tynagh, he actually played--

00:23:36.880 --> 00:23:42.650
and one of the oldest of the
gray Paolo Soprani accordions.

00:23:42.650 --> 00:23:43.950
It was just a beautiful thing.

00:23:43.950 --> 00:23:46.030
He bought it from a tanker.

00:23:46.030 --> 00:23:51.230 position:56%
His mother was ready to-- His mother
didn't talk to him for about a month

00:23:51.230 --> 00:23:52.950
after he bought this accordion.

00:23:52.950 --> 00:23:57.650
He paid 50 pounds and gave the
tinker a brand new accordion

00:23:57.650 --> 00:23:59.130
and his mother was mad.

00:23:59.130 --> 00:24:01.850
And then she realized
that he was right.

00:24:01.850 --> 00:24:07.550
So there are-- It kind of reflect.

00:24:07.550 --> 00:24:10.520
It kind of hearkens back almost

00:24:10.520 --> 00:24:15.140
to where the Anglo concertina
is very similar to that.

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:16.440
And of course the great Joe,

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:19.890
the great Joe Burke also
from in around Loughrea.

00:24:19.890 --> 00:24:26.740
So there was a really
incredible really well-rooted,

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:34.170
highly respected group-- core group
of these musicians in eats Galway,

00:24:34.170 --> 00:24:36.760
so-- And that's what I
was really privileged to--

00:24:36.760 --> 00:24:39.430
John Joe Forde would be another
one of these box players.

00:24:39.430 --> 00:24:41.960
Ned Coleman was one of
the flute players there.

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:46.880
The Ballinakill Ceili Band,
the Leitrim Ceili Band,

00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:49.340
these were beautiful dance bands

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:51.610
that actually got a
chance to record.

00:24:51.610 --> 00:24:54.140
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: But
