And he goes, oh, I'm
sorry, my hand hurts.

00:28:30.250 --> 00:28:32.240
And it was like a joke.

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:34.130
And I thought, well, never--

00:28:34.130 --> 00:28:35.760
I'm never going to make
that mistake again.

00:28:35.760 --> 00:28:40.360
So I'd watch players
and I'd watch them play.

00:28:40.360 --> 00:28:46.010
But when Sean came
over, he was just great.

00:28:46.010 --> 00:28:49.500
He was just a really great,
great guy and he just--

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:52.750
He told me that day in the house,
he says you're going to be--

00:28:52.750 --> 00:28:54.130
You're going to be a great player.

00:28:54.130 --> 00:28:56.970
I was so intimidated when I met
him there that I actually went

00:28:56.970 --> 00:29:01.150
up to my room and did homework.

00:29:01.150 --> 00:29:04.440
This is not my style at all.

00:29:04.440 --> 00:29:05.970
It's like the only
time I ever did that.

00:29:05.970 --> 00:29:08.940
And he came up and he came up

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:12.030
and he said you're going
to be a great player.

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:15.050
And it's funny, Joe Cooley
told me that same thing.

00:29:15.050 --> 00:29:18.240 position:56%
They were so anxious, they were so--

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:21.440
it was so important to
them to share this culture.

00:29:21.440 --> 00:29:24.500
And then as I got to know
Sean, I was up in there--

00:29:24.500 --> 00:29:27.620 position:56%
I went to the Catskills and there
is Sean McGlynn up my uncle's house.

00:29:27.620 --> 00:29:28.920
He had a pickup truck.

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:31.380
And we went for a ride in
the pickup truck just driving

00:29:31.380 --> 00:29:33.100
around up in the mountains.

00:29:33.100 --> 00:29:34.400
Where do you live?

00:29:34.400 --> 00:29:37.080
And then next thing, we stopped
at this little gas station.

00:29:37.080 --> 00:29:41.180
I remember this stuff, I was
maybe 14 and a half years old

00:29:41.180 --> 00:29:42.480
and it had a clutch in it.

00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:44.250
I was going, boy, this is terrific.

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:48.450
And by the time we got back to
the house, he was my best friend.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:51.240
And it's just-- That's
just kind of how it was.

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:53.830
So, yeah, it was really
something-- He loved coming down.

00:29:53.830 --> 00:29:55.130
He loved coming down.

00:29:55.130 --> 00:29:56.480
When he meet Dr. Moloney.

00:29:56.480 --> 00:30:01.270
I guess Mick was probably-- I
guess he had gotten his scholarship

00:30:01.270 --> 00:30:04.980
to do his graduate work over at
Penn-- that's where you went.

00:30:04.980 --> 00:30:11.330
And Sean just loved
coming down and he was--

00:30:11.330 --> 00:30:15.200 position:56%
He'd come down and just enjoy the
couple of pubs that they would work.

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:20.690
And then-- And they got to play the
19...the bicentennial folk festival

00:30:20.690 --> 00:30:22.890
and Jimmy Carter was in it.

00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:27.410 position:56%
My God, but-- Think about the people
who there, and the Irish that came

00:30:27.410 --> 00:30:30.620
out it was, it was--
I mean just the Irish.

00:30:30.620 --> 00:30:32.040
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, you must
have gone to that, right?

00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:33.340
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: We?

00:30:33.340 --> 00:30:34.640
Yeah. Mick got us.

00:30:34.640 --> 00:30:39.160
He got us to go and we were like
we were doing the Dubliner gig

00:30:39.160 --> 00:30:44.400
and we werent well behaved at all
and we missed half of everything.

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:45.700
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So
we're talking about the--

00:30:45.700 --> 00:30:47.000
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
We were frustrated.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:48.300
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: -- what's now
the Smithsonian Folklife Festival

00:30:48.300 --> 00:30:50.260
but then was the Festival
of American Folklife

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:53.420
in 1976 was a particularly
big festival

00:30:53.420 --> 00:30:54.720
because of the bicentennial.

00:30:54.720 --> 00:30:56.020
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
It was unbelievable.

00:30:56.020 --> 00:31:01.010
And the great Junior Crehan
came out from Milltown Malbay.

00:31:01.010 --> 00:31:04.490
And Sean was the featured--

00:31:04.490 --> 00:31:07.200
Thought that it was great
that I was his student there

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:11.220
but Sean was the box--
Sean was the box player.

00:31:11.220 --> 00:31:14.400
They brought Denis Doody,
the great Kerry box player

00:31:14.400 --> 00:31:19.390
down as well, and De Danann.

00:31:19.390 --> 00:31:22.590
Michael Flatley was
actually the featured dancer.

00:31:22.590 --> 00:31:26.590
It was like, what is going
on here, you know, so.

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:30.530
And we were-- we were very lucky
at the time just playing there

00:31:30.530 --> 00:31:33.380
in the Dubliner-- thank
goodness, nobody got hurt.

00:31:33.380 --> 00:31:34.680
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:31:34.680 --> 00:31:35.980
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: You know,

00:31:35.980 --> 00:31:37.720
there is no harm done
really, I don't think.

00:31:37.720 --> 00:31:39.020
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:31:39.020 --> 00:31:41.710
So, but before that happened, I
mean you had to first of all--

00:31:41.710 --> 00:31:45.320
So you met McGlynn and
became good friends.

00:31:45.320 --> 00:31:46.620
And--

00:31:46.620 --> 00:31:47.920
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
And he was my mentor,

00:31:47.920 --> 00:31:51.190
he was my absolute--
He was my best friend.

00:31:51.190 --> 00:31:52.630
And he was my best man.

00:31:52.630 --> 00:31:53.930
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:31:53.930 --> 00:31:56.980
And did you take formal
lessons with him

00:31:56.980 --> 00:32:00.960
or did you just watch him
play and play alongside him?

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:02.260
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
There was no such thing

00:32:02.260 --> 00:32:06.620
as getting a formal lesson on-- for
the Irish accordion at the time,

00:32:06.620 --> 00:32:08.330
which is really something
in Brooklyn,

00:32:08.330 --> 00:32:10.200
that there were a bunch of them.

00:32:10.200 --> 00:32:13.550
Not a bunch but a few
Italian immigrants

00:32:13.550 --> 00:32:14.920
that were able to play
the accordion.

00:32:14.920 --> 00:32:18.440
So there are a bunch of
young kids playing "Lady

00:32:18.440 --> 00:32:20.040
of Spain" on the piano accordion.

00:32:20.040 --> 00:32:21.340
I never quite got that.

00:32:21.340 --> 00:32:22.760
I didn't want to do that.

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:25.910
But I loved-- I just loved
the way McGlynn played.

00:32:25.910 --> 00:32:28.510
It was-- He said there's
a-- There is a roughness,

00:32:28.510 --> 00:32:31.640
there's a certain roughness in it,
he says, and the people liked that.

00:32:31.640 --> 00:32:36.960
And he had-- he had big-- He's
a very strong man but the tips

00:32:36.960 --> 00:32:40.760
of his fingers were very small.

00:32:40.760 --> 00:32:43.250 position:56%
He had great dexterity in his hands.

00:32:43.250 --> 00:32:47.550
And he loved continental
accordion music and we--

00:32:47.550 --> 00:32:51.490
if you heard the great
jazz players now,

00:32:51.490 --> 00:32:53.500
the great chromatic jazz players,

00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:56.050
I mean all over the place,
a lot of stuff going on.

00:32:56.050 --> 00:32:57.640
And there was a book called "The
Bourbon Method" [assumed spelling].

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:01.510
So you could open this book
and sit out there and you go--

00:33:01.510 --> 00:33:05.040
[ Singing ]

00:33:05.040 --> 00:33:08.810
And he just ended it
with that, lovely.

00:33:08.810 --> 00:33:11.330
And I-- that he'd-- He
was able to read it.

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:16.860
He went to -- Mario Tacca
was the great accordionist

00:33:16.860 --> 00:33:20.240
in the Upstate New York area,
and Sean would drive up there

00:33:20.240 --> 00:33:24.430
for a lesson when he had the time
and he got a continental accordion.

00:33:24.430 --> 00:33:29.930
And he loved that technique
that the Italians had figured

00:33:29.930 --> 00:33:31.230
out for the continental accordion.

00:33:31.230 --> 00:33:35.720
But there really wasn't technique
for the Irish accordion and he--

00:33:35.720 --> 00:33:38.350
Sean said, well, it's
great for the Irish music

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:41.100
but it's really-- it's just a toy.

00:33:41.100 --> 00:33:43.520
It's not a real instrument.

00:33:43.520 --> 00:33:46.810
And I guess in a way
he's kind of right,

00:33:46.810 --> 00:33:48.490
you know, because that's true.

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:50.250
It's older, it's an
older type of music.

00:33:50.250 --> 00:33:51.790
And there was no technique.

00:33:51.790 --> 00:33:53.460
But that's kind of--
that kind of spark there.

00:33:53.460 --> 00:33:58.380
I remember sitting in my
uncle's house and up in Leeds

00:33:58.380 --> 00:34:03.230 position:56%
and Sean's wife and the Leonards
and my uncle, they were all down in,

00:34:03.230 --> 00:34:05.900
down in Gilfeather's Sligo
House and having a great time

00:34:05.900 --> 00:34:07.730
with the show bands
and it was great fun.

00:34:07.730 --> 00:34:12.550
And Sean and I were sitting
in the kitchen talking away.

00:34:12.550 --> 00:34:16.530
You can hear the crickets
outside of the screen and the door

00:34:16.530 --> 00:34:20.990
and the moths were coming
up against the door.

00:34:20.990 --> 00:34:23.180
Then the little things you
can hear going on out there.

00:34:23.180 --> 00:34:26.840
And we were sitting there trying to
figure out the fingering for a tune

00:34:26.840 --> 00:34:29.690
that was written by
the great Martin Wynne

00:34:29.690 --> 00:34:31.620
from Sligo who lived in the Bronx.

00:34:31.620 --> 00:34:33.590
And we were trying to-- the fiddle
player, we're trying to figure

00:34:33.590 --> 00:34:38.120
out how can you take-- how-- and
we just sat there trying to figure

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:40.320
out how to cover about
an octave and a half--

00:34:40.320 --> 00:34:47.790
octave and a half and about
eight, you know, nine notes to get

00:34:47.790 --> 00:34:49.970
down there, how are you
supposed to do that.

00:34:49.970 --> 00:34:51.270
And we finally figured it out.

00:34:51.270 --> 00:34:54.310
And Sean says, he says, there's
the difference right there.

00:34:54.310 --> 00:34:55.610
And I said, what's that?

00:34:55.610 --> 00:34:58.040
He says that-- there they are,
they're all down there in the bar

00:34:58.040 --> 00:35:00.120
and they're having a great
time singing and dancing

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:03.470
and here we are worried
about one note.

00:35:03.470 --> 00:35:09.240
And there was just a great-- there
was just great logic to that.

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:10.540
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: There's
a lesson in it.

00:35:10.540 --> 00:35:11.840
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: So-- yeah.

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:13.880
So we had a-- he had a great love
for technique and he was fascinated

00:35:13.880 --> 00:35:18.830
by it, and he would then show me
show so much as, well he'd go,

00:35:18.830 --> 00:35:20.260
how do you think we--
how could you--

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:22.460
you know, after we knew each
other for a little while,

00:35:22.460 --> 00:35:24.460
how do you think-- what
would you do there?

00:35:24.460 --> 00:35:25.760
And we would sit and just figure

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:30.330
out these finger patterns
kind of like dancing.

00:35:30.330 --> 00:35:33.140
I'm like instead of using two
feet to dance, you have fingers,

00:35:33.140 --> 00:35:35.580
which is kind of nice, yeah.

00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:38.300
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Now, you mentioned
McGlynn's beautiful accordion.

00:35:38.300 --> 00:35:41.790
And if I'm not mistaken,
you inherited that.

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:43.090
Is that--

00:35:43.090 --> 00:35:44.390
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: I did.

00:35:44.390 --> 00:35:45.690
We had an argument one night.

00:35:45.690 --> 00:35:48.000
We had a little-- We had a little
bit too much to drink when the--

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.210
when the first Green Fields
tour came to this area

00:35:52.210 --> 00:35:56.960
and they were performing
at Georgetown University.

00:35:56.960 --> 00:35:59.300
And it was a great night.

00:35:59.300 --> 00:36:03.330
And back in those days, they'd stay
with whoever would put them up.

00:36:03.330 --> 00:36:05.550
And they all got kind of bored.

00:36:05.550 --> 00:36:10.390
So they decided-- one by one, they
would say, Billy, can I come over?

00:36:10.390 --> 00:36:13.520
It's OK. I think I have room
at your-- at the apartment.

00:36:13.520 --> 00:36:17.960
So, we ended up-- I ended up
with the whole Green Fields.

00:36:17.960 --> 00:36:19.260
The first Green Field--

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:20.570
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: There's
like 12 people in that or--

00:36:20.570 --> 00:36:23.020
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
Yeah, Liz Carroll,

00:36:23.020 --> 00:36:25.140
Michael Flatley, Donny Golden.

00:36:25.140 --> 00:36:28.350
It might have been the second
Green Fields tour, sorry for that.

00:36:28.350 --> 00:36:30.910
Sean McGlynn, Jack Coen.

00:36:30.910 --> 00:36:33.000
Who else? There was a great piper.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:37.680
Of course, Mick was-- he
was out paving the way.

00:36:37.680 --> 00:36:41.530
All the other guys were
partying like way too much.

00:36:41.530 --> 00:36:46.510
And so, we got in an argument, Sean
and I, about who loved who more.

00:36:46.510 --> 00:36:49.810
[ Laughter ]

00:36:49.810 --> 00:36:52.270
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey:
It's pretty adorable.

00:36:52.270 --> 00:36:53.570
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah.

00:36:53.570 --> 00:36:55.410
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Who won?

00:36:55.410 --> 00:36:56.960
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: And he
said, he said, "Well, OK."

00:36:56.960 --> 00:36:59.270
He says, "You think you love me."

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:04.200
He says, "The day I die you're
getting my gray accordion."

00:37:04.200 --> 00:37:05.550
And that was the end
of the argument.

00:37:05.550 --> 00:37:06.850
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:37:06.850 --> 00:37:10.400
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: That was-- And
Flatley, Michael Flatley was like,

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:11.980
"Come on, where's--
what's crackin'?"

00:37:11.980 --> 00:37:16.020
They were having 902s,
they had gone to Jamaica.

00:37:16.020 --> 00:37:17.320
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: 702s.

00:37:17.320 --> 00:37:18.620
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: 702s.

00:37:18.620 --> 00:37:19.920
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: It's all right.

00:37:19.920 --> 00:37:21.220
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: So
you knew the actual name?

00:37:21.220 --> 00:37:22.520
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: I
named the drink , so--

00:37:22.520 --> 00:37:23.820
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: You named it?

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:25.120
So they-- So they would take
a bottle of rum and Coca-Cola

00:37:25.120 --> 00:37:26.420
and a scoop of ice cream.

00:37:26.420 --> 00:37:27.720
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: Gosh.

00:37:27.720 --> 00:37:29.410
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: And they
were talking about these 702s,

00:37:29.410 --> 00:37:33.040
and then Sean actually made one
with all the drama, you know,

00:37:33.040 --> 00:37:34.370
you'd think you were watching one

00:37:34.370 --> 00:37:36.800
of these cooking shows,
on public television--

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:38.100
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Jack
was in it on that too.

00:37:38.100 --> 00:37:39.400
It's Jack and Mike and Sean.

00:37:39.400 --> 00:37:41.370
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, and the
big scoop of ice room plopped right

00:37:41.370 --> 00:37:44.980
in the middle of it and we all
thought it was terrific, 702s.

00:37:44.980 --> 00:37:46.280
Well now--

00:37:46.280 --> 00:37:47.690
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: All right.

00:37:47.690 --> 00:37:48.990
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: So, no one,

00:37:48.990 --> 00:37:51.550
whether he would never
ever think-- nobody.

00:37:51.550 --> 00:37:53.640 position:56%
Well, there were a couple of fellas.

00:37:53.640 --> 00:38:00.170
Martin Mulvihill, again, again, you
know, another National Heritage--

00:38:00.170 --> 00:38:02.650
and I pled for years down
hear with Brendan Mulvihill,

00:38:02.650 --> 00:38:05.140
still one of my best friends.

00:38:05.140 --> 00:38:09.870
But Martin managed to make a
modest living teaching Irish music.

00:38:09.870 --> 00:38:11.340
And my friend Maureen Glynn--

00:38:11.340 --> 00:38:12.640
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:16.120
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: -- inherited
her father's music school.

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:18.820
There was another fella,
Pete Kelly from Galway.

00:38:18.820 --> 00:38:21.190
And he did pretty good at it too.

00:38:21.190 --> 00:38:29.090
But Sean would never, in a million
years, take any money from anybody

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:31.880 position:56%
if they wanted to learn Irish music.

00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:37.610
It was not an issue, it just
wasn't-- it wasn't how it is done.

00:38:37.610 --> 00:38:38.910
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:38:38.910 --> 00:38:42.460
So, did you, when you were living
in New York, did you know Martin?

00:38:42.460 --> 00:38:44.730
Did you know of his
teaching and all of that?

00:38:44.730 --> 00:38:46.540
That that was going on?

00:38:46.540 --> 00:38:49.740
Because I remember, when I was
growing up, he was still active,

00:38:49.740 --> 00:38:51.040
but he must have been active.

00:38:51.040 --> 00:38:52.340
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Oh,
Martin is a great guy.

00:38:52.340 --> 00:38:53.640
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:54.940
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah.

00:38:54.940 --> 00:38:56.780
Martin was such a gentleman
from Glin.

00:38:56.780 --> 00:38:59.930
Yeah. And he did-- he
had a natural gift.

00:38:59.930 --> 00:39:03.550
He's kind of like Mick Gavin.

00:39:03.550 --> 00:39:08.020
That's who-- that's how--
Mick Gavin from County Clare.

00:39:08.020 --> 00:39:13.800
Sean is great friends with Mick's
sons, Mick would be about my age.

00:39:13.800 --> 00:39:18.630
But he is of these gentlemen, he
can-- he's a lovely fiddle player.

00:39:18.630 --> 00:39:22.980
He's a nice box player in this
Cooley-- in the Cooley style,

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:26.870
the D tuning, and he's--
He can get an old tune

00:39:26.870 --> 00:39:28.540
out of a whistle and a flute.

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.230
But the thing-- he's kind of like
Mitch Fanning, who's right here.

00:39:31.230 --> 00:39:32.530
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:39:32.530 --> 00:39:35.700
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: He's one these
people that is just so generous

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:42.750
with his art, you know,
with his music.

00:39:42.750 --> 00:39:50.470
He doesn't allow himself to impede,
you know, a student's growth.

00:39:50.470 --> 00:39:54.420
So, you know, Gavin--
Mick Gavin is that way.

00:39:54.420 --> 00:40:01.410 position:56%
But Martin, Martin Mulvihill would--
he would just grill these students

00:40:01.410 --> 00:40:06.780 position:56%
with all the competitions were
getting, were gaining an importance.

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:09.980
My nieces are all into
this competition.

00:40:09.980 --> 00:40:12.900
But you had a real good
chance back in those days

00:40:12.900 --> 00:40:17.410
if you were a student
of Martin Mulvihill.

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:19.350
You were going to do all right.

00:40:19.350 --> 00:40:24.020
I'm a huge repertoire, a huge
store of music, and really, really,

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:28.700
really highly, highly regarded
and respected in Ireland.

00:40:31.020 --> 00:40:33.410
Martin Mulvihill was hilarious.

00:40:33.410 --> 00:40:34.710
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:40:34.710 --> 00:40:38.800
So, at some point, you ended up
moving first to the Washington area

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:40.330
and then you settled in Baltimore?

00:40:40.330 --> 00:40:41.630
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah.

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:42.930
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: How
did that come about?

00:40:42.930 --> 00:40:44.230
How did you come to
Washington first?

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:46.090
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Well, it
started a little bit before that.

00:40:46.090 --> 00:40:50.340
Johnny Cronin from Gneeveguilla
from County Kerry, one of the--

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:54.390
Sliabh Luachra player, Paddy--
the brother of Paddy Cronin.

00:40:54.390 --> 00:40:56.580
Paddy Cronin is probably are--

00:40:56.580 --> 00:41:03.880
he's arguably the most renowned
of the fiddlers of our time.

00:41:03.880 --> 00:41:05.250
He passed away recently.

00:41:05.250 --> 00:41:08.190
He gets-- It wasn't that he
was a whiz kid or something,

00:41:08.190 --> 00:41:11.970
but Paddy just played
the music so right,

00:41:11.970 --> 00:41:15.340
and it was like so
close to what it is.

00:41:15.340 --> 00:41:19.560
And so Johnny, Johnny was
a sandhogger in New York.

00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:22.100
And he was great friends
with Joe Cooley.

00:41:22.100 --> 00:41:26.260
He was, again, hilarious
kind of guy.

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:29.210
And he's been in a bit of drinking
problem I guess you would say,

00:41:29.210 --> 00:41:32.880
but a huge, huge, huge, huge
heart, very, very generous man.

00:41:32.880 --> 00:41:36.400 position:56%
And he said to me, "Billy, you come
and get my Irish accent is no good."

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:39.220
"Billy, you'll come to--
you'll come and you'll pay.

00:41:39.220 --> 00:41:43.850
You'll play in the Bunratty Pub
with me and they'll give you $50

00:41:43.850 --> 00:41:46.210
and all the Heineken
that you could drink."

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:49.290
And this was like unheard of
that you could go out on a Friday

00:41:49.290 --> 00:41:53.810
or Saturday night and play
and people would be in there,

00:41:53.810 --> 00:41:57.140
they wouldn't like
tell you to be quiet.

00:41:57.140 --> 00:41:58.690
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: They'd pay you.

00:41:58.690 --> 00:42:01.980
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: The
pay part was unheard of.

00:42:01.980 --> 00:42:03.280
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:05.920 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: You know, you--
the only place we ever played was

00:42:05.920 --> 00:42:08.720
in the basements in the back where
we weren't bothering anybody.

00:42:08.720 --> 00:42:16.960
So to be playing in, you know, on
a stage, and as I first started

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:21.930
to cut my teeth there, I ended
up filling in for Joe Burke.

00:42:21.930 --> 00:42:25.760
Filling in for Joe Burke,
you know, with Andy McGann.

00:42:25.760 --> 00:42:35.400
Andy McGann and Joe Burke and
Felix Dolan created the sound

00:42:35.400 --> 00:42:38.660
that Irish music still
has to this very day.

00:42:38.660 --> 00:42:42.540
Myself and Joanie Madden and
Brian Conway and Brendan Dolan.

00:42:42.540 --> 00:42:44.220
We have a recording out,
"The Pride of New York,"

00:42:44.220 --> 00:42:45.520
and I talk about this Irish style.

00:42:45.520 --> 00:42:49.940
It was Joe Burke and Andy
McGann and Felix Dolan.

00:42:49.940 --> 00:42:54.150
So, all this crazy stuff is
going on in the Bunratty Pub

00:42:54.150 --> 00:42:57.990
or maybe they would go out and
play ceilis or something like that.

00:42:57.990 --> 00:43:06.870
But this was a real gig in an Irish
bar that, you know, I would say I--

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:10.650
for the year-- the two years
that I played there, maybe three

00:43:10.650 --> 00:43:15.560
or four really, really fantastic
fights, you know, the immigrants.

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:18.120
There was one night these
two guys were arguing

00:43:18.120 --> 00:43:20.550
about who was the better
football team.

00:43:20.550 --> 00:43:23.760
Was it the Irish football,
was it the Longford team,

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:27.220
or was it the Roscommon team,
whatever they were arguing about,

00:43:27.220 --> 00:43:28.520
and they started to fight.

00:43:28.520 --> 00:43:30.670
But they were gentlemen, so
they brought the fight outside.

00:43:30.670 --> 00:43:35.170
And there was-- and it was a-- and
then-- and it's kind of tragic.

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:38.540
There's a-- they went out and they
go down and they found a vacant lot

00:43:38.540 --> 00:43:40.880
so they wouldn't be disturbing the
traffic when they have the fight.

00:43:40.880 --> 00:43:45.400
And then finally, one of them
won and the other one was dead.

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:46.700
So, this was kind of new.

00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:49.240
It was-- This was the
real Irish bar.

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:50.540
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:43:50.540 --> 00:43:52.650
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: And
so, it was a pretty fight.

00:43:52.650 --> 00:43:56.720
One night, Johnny Cronin, I
went in looking for Johnny

00:43:56.720 --> 00:44:00.310
and I found them asleep
under one of the tables.

00:44:00.310 --> 00:44:06.010
He had an expression that well, the
ceiling in this house is very low.

00:44:06.010 --> 00:44:08.380
And so it was like pretty funny.

00:44:08.380 --> 00:44:09.680
He was a pretty funny guy.

00:44:09.680 --> 00:44:14.350
But I was in there playing in
the bar and there was a fiddler,

00:44:14.350 --> 00:44:17.850
an Irish-American fiddler
named Jack Riordan.

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:22.320
And you wouldn't know if
he was an Irish-American

00:44:22.320 --> 00:44:27.980 position:56%
and you wouldn't know an
Irish-American might be an immigrant

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:33.070
that's a citizen or it might
be the child of an immigrant.

00:44:33.070 --> 00:44:34.650
It was kind of shady.

00:44:34.650 --> 00:44:36.560
But I kind of think--
I mean Jack was--

00:44:36.560 --> 00:44:38.970
I think he was an Irish-American
and he played the fiddle.

00:44:38.970 --> 00:44:44.410
And his daughter, Peggy Riordan,
was a lovely fiddler player too

00:44:44.410 --> 00:44:48.870
and she knew all the fellows
like in the various ceili bands

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:50.170
that would come out,

00:44:50.170 --> 00:44:54.480
the old Liverpool Ceili Band,
she knew all these guys.

00:44:54.480 --> 00:45:02.970
But Lou-- So, Peggy came up to the
Bunratty on a quiet kind of night

00:45:02.970 --> 00:45:06.890
and she brought this fellow
with her and she said,

00:45:06.890 --> 00:45:11.030
this is my friend Lou Thompson.

00:45:11.030 --> 00:45:13.840
And she brought this guy to
meet me and they'd come up.

00:45:13.840 --> 00:45:16.150
Peggy at-- Peggy wasn't
living in the Bronx

00:45:16.150 --> 00:45:18.280
for a while, so how are you doing.

00:45:18.280 --> 00:45:19.580
Where did you go?

00:45:19.580 --> 00:45:20.880
I went to Washington.

00:45:20.880 --> 00:45:22.180
Oh, that's nice.

00:45:22.180 --> 00:45:23.480
How-- Do you like Washington?

00:45:23.480 --> 00:45:24.780
And the next time I'd
see her, she's say well--

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.850
oh, well I live in
northern-- I live in Virginia.

00:45:26.850 --> 00:45:29.180
I was going, I thought
you lived in Washington.

00:45:29.180 --> 00:45:30.930
I didn't do well in geography.

00:45:30.930 --> 00:45:33.850
She said, I thought--
now I moved in Virginia.

00:45:33.850 --> 00:45:35.150
Oh, really.

00:45:35.150 --> 00:45:36.450
The next time I saw her, I live

00:45:36.450 --> 00:45:37.750
in Washington and--
or, I live in Maryland.

00:45:37.750 --> 00:45:39.360
I was going, wow, she's
really moving around.

00:45:39.360 --> 00:45:42.730
I didn't realize she's just
hopping around this tri-state area.

00:45:42.730 --> 00:45:48.680
She said-- so, she said, one or
two-- She introduced me to this--

00:45:48.680 --> 00:45:51.510
Father Lou Thompson, the priest,

00:45:51.510 --> 00:45:56.550 position:56%
who was stationed here I guess I
would say or he was in a pretty kind

00:45:56.550 --> 00:45:59.560
of progressive Catholic order.

00:45:59.560 --> 00:46:01.650
And it was very small order.

00:46:01.650 --> 00:46:05.790
And he did his-- he actually
did his undergraduate work

00:46:05.790 --> 00:46:09.740 position:56%
in community organization, so he's
pretty really interesting character.

00:46:09.740 --> 00:46:12.810
And again, he played
kind of in this style

00:46:12.810 --> 00:46:18.540
that Joe Derrane played the old
Walters and Baldoni accordion.

00:46:18.540 --> 00:46:25.380
So she wanted me to meet Father
Lou and he said, you know, he said,

00:46:25.380 --> 00:46:28.590
why don't you come
down to Washington to--

00:46:28.590 --> 00:46:32.420
sometime and we can have
a ceili and you can come

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:33.970
down to see what it's like.

00:46:33.970 --> 00:46:40.700
So I did and I got to fly from
LaGuardia into national airport.

00:46:40.700 --> 00:46:44.990
So if you can picture LaGuardia,
I drove across the Bronx

00:46:44.990 --> 00:46:49.090
through Queens with all that
stuff going on, you know,

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:50.390
and made it to LaGuardia.

00:46:50.390 --> 00:46:54.130
I left the car there,
paid a fortune to park it,

00:46:54.130 --> 00:46:56.250
just the whole experience
you're doing--

00:46:56.250 --> 00:46:59.600
and I got off at national
airport and it was sort

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:01.630
of like the Wizard of Oz.

00:47:01.630 --> 00:47:04.490
All of a sudden everything
in color and I was like,

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:06.160
what's all this going on?

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:13.570
And she picked me up in a
brand new 1976 Chevy Malibu.

00:47:13.570 --> 00:47:14.870
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

00:47:14.870 --> 00:47:16.170
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
I remember that.

00:47:16.170 --> 00:47:17.470
I remember that.

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:20.540
And we drove up along the Potomac
and I was going, what's going on.

00:47:20.540 --> 00:47:24.010
And we went and I played the ceili

00:47:24.010 --> 00:47:29.420
and I met the Winch brothers,
Jesse and Terry Winch.

00:47:29.420 --> 00:47:34.470
And of course Peggy had Terry
and they are from the Bronx too.

00:47:34.470 --> 00:47:38.010
Jesse and Terry were both
very, very well educated.

00:47:38.010 --> 00:47:40.520
Very, very intelligent men.

00:47:40.520 --> 00:47:42.700
Terry is a poet and a box player.

00:47:42.700 --> 00:47:46.720
Jesse is a lovely bodhran player.

00:47:46.720 --> 00:47:48.020
And there was a couple
of other guys.

00:47:48.020 --> 00:47:50.670
Mark Quinn played the accordion
and he was from Rockaway.

00:47:50.670 --> 00:47:56.280
Mark had actually got tired of
living in New York and he went

00:47:56.280 --> 00:48:00.360
to the train station and
he goes, I have 50 bucks.

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:02.030 position:56%
He said, you know, where can you go?

00:48:02.030 --> 00:48:04.840
And the guy, the guy said,
you can go to Washington.

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:06.140
So he did.

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:10.660
And he went into the bar
on 13th, Matt Kane's.

00:48:10.660 --> 00:48:14.800
And he told the bar-- And he told
the cabbie, is there an Irish bar?

00:48:14.800 --> 00:48:16.100
And he brought him to Matt Kane's.

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:18.710
And he went in and he found his way

00:48:18.710 --> 00:48:21.410
and became a resident
with his accordion.

00:48:21.410 --> 00:48:24.500
So, they have this
little nucleus and that--

00:48:24.500 --> 00:48:25.800
I guess they were talking about it.

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:27.260
How can we get-- What
do you think we can do

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:30.150
to get the real music there
because Peggy really--

00:48:30.150 --> 00:48:32.690
Peggy was homesick for the music.

00:48:32.690 --> 00:48:34.000
And so they invited me.

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:36.430
That's kind of what happened--
I came down and played the ceili

00:48:36.430 --> 00:48:39.100
and I told Father Lou,
I said, if you could--

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:42.020
if you can swing me a job
down here, a clerk's job

00:48:42.020 --> 00:48:44.650
or something, I'll come down.

00:48:44.650 --> 00:48:53.280
And it was right then that this
Irish pub phenomenon was starting

00:48:53.280 --> 00:48:55.100
to take shape.

00:48:55.100 --> 00:48:59.200
It was between Guinness
and Harp breweries,

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:00.870
they came up with this
idea where you're going

00:49:00.870 --> 00:49:03.060
to have an Irish themed
bar and it would be just

00:49:03.060 --> 00:49:04.720
like Dublin, blah, blah, blah.

00:49:04.720 --> 00:49:07.260
And he called it the
Dubliner and terrific.

00:49:07.260 --> 00:49:08.720
And Matt Kane's was the first.

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:12.570
There was another one in New
York, the John Barleycorn.

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:14.190 position:56%
I played there in midtown Manhattan.

00:49:14.190 --> 00:49:16.680
It looked like a little pub and
it was in the middle of Manhattan.

00:49:16.680 --> 00:49:21.110
But the Dubliner was
like serious business.

00:49:21.110 --> 00:49:25.010
And I guess though at that point,
on Capitol Hill was like, well,

00:49:25.010 --> 00:49:26.370
kind of-- well, kind of tough.

00:49:26.370 --> 00:49:28.250 position:56%
We never had any trouble there but--

00:49:28.250 --> 00:49:30.640
there was kind of more
postal workers

00:49:30.640 --> 00:49:31.940
and stuff hanging around there.

00:49:31.940 --> 00:49:33.520
There was nothing cool about it,

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:36.130
except that the Capitol
Building was right there.

00:49:36.130 --> 00:49:44.300
But we really had a tremendous
amount of fun and these various--

00:49:44.300 --> 00:49:47.000
I guess the other thing that
was so cool about it was people

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:51.790
like Alan Jabbour, am
I saying that right?

00:49:51.790 --> 00:49:53.690
It was--

00:49:53.690 --> 00:49:54.990
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Rinzler.

00:49:54.990 --> 00:49:56.290
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Ralph Rinzler.

00:49:56.290 --> 00:50:00.000
Mick, Mick Moloney again was
coming back and forth and working

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.420
on his degree in Georgetown.

00:50:02.420 --> 00:50:07.860
So there were these really
interesting folklorists

00:50:07.860 --> 00:50:10.390
and ethnomusicologists, and
it was like a whole new thing.

00:50:10.390 --> 00:50:15.020
And, you know-- But I
was there and, you know,

00:50:15.020 --> 00:50:16.420
I was playing with
Brendan Mulvihill.

00:50:16.420 --> 00:50:17.910
I asked Brendan Mulvihill
to come down.

00:50:17.910 --> 00:50:22.870
Brendan was-- especially
at that time,

00:50:22.870 --> 00:50:28.310
he was one of very best Irish
fiddlers in Irish music,

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:30.000
of these young Irish players.

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:31.300
And Andy O'Brien--

00:50:31.300 --> 00:50:33.680
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And we should say
he was the son of Martin Mulvihill,

00:50:33.680 --> 00:50:34.980
the great teacher that
we were talking about.

00:50:34.980 --> 00:50:36.280
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: A son
of Martin Mulvihill, yeah.

00:50:36.280 --> 00:50:37.770
So that's kind of how-- That's
kind of how we came down.

00:50:37.770 --> 00:50:41.700
And then Lou wanted to start
a music school and we did.

00:50:41.700 --> 00:50:43.000
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Well,
you would also just went

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:44.910
about to mention Andy
O'Brien and how he got it all.

00:50:44.910 --> 00:50:47.120
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Andy
O'Brien was from Kerry,

00:50:47.120 --> 00:50:48.420
kind of like Johnny Cronin.

00:50:48.420 --> 00:50:51.150
And Johnny told me, he says,
you have to meet Andy O'Brien,

00:50:51.150 --> 00:50:54.710
he's a great singer and he is
a really good guitar player.

00:50:54.710 --> 00:50:58.380
And I-- My friend Pat Keogh and I
needed a guitar player one night

00:50:58.380 --> 00:51:02.820 position:56%
up in the Bronx before I moved down
and I asked Andy to do-- do the gig.

00:51:02.820 --> 00:51:07.020
And it was the first time I
ever played for money anywhere

00:51:07.020 --> 00:51:10.290
in New York City where
anybody actually clapped.

00:51:10.290 --> 00:51:15.050
And it was Andy-- or Andy
got to play with people

00:51:15.050 --> 00:51:19.960
like Johnny Leary or Denis Murphy.

00:51:19.960 --> 00:51:22.430
He was from this whole
Sliabh Luachra thing

00:51:22.430 --> 00:51:24.350
that was going on in County Clare.

00:51:24.350 --> 00:51:31.020 position:56%
But at the same time, he was stone
mad for the Scottish song tradition,

00:51:31.020 --> 00:51:35.070
the Scottish-- the Scots were
like really, really interested

00:51:35.070 --> 00:51:37.750
with this DADGAD tuning
on the guitar.

00:51:37.750 --> 00:51:39.830
Archie Fisher, Andy O'Brien--

00:51:39.830 --> 00:51:41.130
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Dick Gaughan--

00:51:41.130 --> 00:51:42.780
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: And between
Archie Fisher and Dick Gaughan

00:51:42.780 --> 00:51:50.510 position:56%
and Andy Irvine was kind of this,
you know, with Planxty or, you know.

00:51:50.510 --> 00:51:54.330
This whole thing that was going on,
Andy was like a huge fan of that.

00:51:54.330 --> 00:51:57.800 position:56%
And he had come out, he wanted--
Andy wanted to get a job as a welder

00:51:57.800 --> 00:52:00.190
when he came out and he was
just about ready to give

00:52:00.190 --> 00:52:04.310 position:56%
up when we got-- when we called him.

00:52:04.310 --> 00:52:09.880 position:56%
In fact, the first time, the first
week that we played in the Dubliner,

00:52:09.880 --> 00:52:14.280
Andy used a subway token and--

00:52:14.280 --> 00:52:15.580
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: From New York,

00:52:15.580 --> 00:52:16.880
because there was no
subway on DC that--

00:52:16.880 --> 00:52:20.300 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, and he
used the subway token to do the gig.

00:52:20.300 --> 00:52:23.820
And when we got paid, we got $300.

00:52:23.820 --> 00:52:26.050
It was really very
big money at the time.

00:52:26.050 --> 00:52:27.410
We thought anyway.

00:52:27.410 --> 00:52:29.610
And Andy counted it and counted it.

00:52:29.610 --> 00:52:30.960
And I said, Andy, what
are you going to--

00:52:30.960 --> 00:52:33.620
because he was from County
Kerry, there is nothing there.

00:52:33.620 --> 00:52:38.560
There was cows and, you know,
we're talking Kerry-- woo!

00:52:38.560 --> 00:52:40.950
And he was going-- He was
counting it like that.

00:52:40.950 --> 00:52:43.400
And I said, Andy, what are you
going to do with all your money?

00:52:43.400 --> 00:52:47.220
And he says, I'm going to go
out and I'm going to buy a pick.

00:52:47.220 --> 00:52:48.520
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Nice.

00:52:48.520 --> 00:52:49.820
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: He's just--
it was just a subway token.

00:52:49.820 --> 00:52:51.120
He never let on.

00:52:51.120 --> 00:52:52.570
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, one of the
tricks to that by the way is

00:52:52.570 --> 00:52:54.920
if you have a whole bunch of
tune players on the stage,

00:52:54.920 --> 00:52:57.540
the music never stops
so no one can ever clap.

00:52:57.540 --> 00:53:01.120
But if you have a singer, that
song is going to end, right?

00:53:01.120 --> 00:53:02.420
So--

00:53:02.420 --> 00:53:05.190
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, I
guess the cool thing about it was

00:53:05.190 --> 00:53:09.900
to survive in the bar scene,
and none of us were, you know,

00:53:09.900 --> 00:53:15.600
it's a kind of-- it's a
trade, it's a skill, you know.

