01:03:56.660 --> 01:03:57.960
They both learned to
dance from Peggy.

01:03:57.960 --> 01:03:59.500
They learned to waltz from Peggy.

01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:04.130
So they-- She danced-- Annie
danced like an Irish-American girl.

01:04:04.130 --> 01:04:07.290
I was just unbelievable.

01:04:07.290 --> 01:04:10.010
But the other thing that was really
funny about it was Peggy used

01:04:10.010 --> 01:04:15.360
to say, you should come up to
Baltimore because there's a girl

01:04:15.360 --> 01:04:19.460
up there and you really should meet
her because you'd really like her.

01:04:19.460 --> 01:04:20.760
And I was, really, what's her name?

01:04:20.760 --> 01:04:24.100
And she says her name
is Franny Caskey.

01:04:24.100 --> 01:04:26.730
And so, what I-- after
the wedding was over,

01:04:26.730 --> 01:04:28.030
how did you enjoy the wedding?

01:04:28.030 --> 01:04:32.010
I said, I met this really-- It's
great, I met this great girl

01:04:32.010 --> 01:04:34.020
and then her name is Annie
Caskey, isn't that the one that?

01:04:34.020 --> 01:04:37.070 position:56%
She says, no, we wanted you-- We
were-- We thought just about Franny.

01:04:37.070 --> 01:04:40.630
So they were off by one
genome thing, you know.

01:04:40.630 --> 01:04:41.930
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

01:04:41.930 --> 01:04:43.230
Right.

01:04:43.230 --> 01:04:44.530
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
Whatever that thing is.

01:04:44.530 --> 01:04:45.830
The only one biological thing.

01:04:45.830 --> 01:04:47.130
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: But--

01:04:47.130 --> 01:04:48.430
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
It was really good.

01:04:48.430 --> 01:04:49.730
Took me a little while to get
her attention and then, you know.

01:04:49.730 --> 01:04:51.030
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Worked out.

01:04:51.030 --> 01:04:52.330
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: She
knew she was out of luck,

01:04:52.330 --> 01:04:53.630
what are you going to do?

01:04:53.630 --> 01:04:56.440 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, yeah, I mean
as you said that during the concert,

01:04:56.440 --> 01:04:59.770
without her maybe, you know,
none of these would have happened

01:04:59.770 --> 01:05:02.160
but certainly some of these
wouldn't have happened.

01:05:02.160 --> 01:05:03.460
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: She is--

01:05:03.460 --> 01:05:04.760
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey:
Technically speaking.

01:05:04.760 --> 01:05:06.060
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Right.

01:05:06.060 --> 01:05:07.360
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: She is the--

01:05:07.360 --> 01:05:08.660
She is the rock, you know,
you can ask the boys.

01:05:08.660 --> 01:05:12.490
She works for the Sisters of
Mercy at the Mercy Medical Center

01:05:12.490 --> 01:05:17.310 position:56%
in Baltimore, which are-- which
were founded by the Sisters of Mercy

01:05:17.310 --> 01:05:19.700
on Baggot Street in Dublin.

01:05:19.700 --> 01:05:24.540
Her father was from the old
10th ward up in Baltimore.

01:05:24.540 --> 01:05:27.880
They were that dirt
poor, and that poorest

01:05:27.880 --> 01:05:30.190
of the poor from the famine times.

01:05:30.190 --> 01:05:34.790
So, yeah, they are a real, you
know, a really great family.

01:05:34.790 --> 01:05:37.720
Her mother is a Polish-American.

01:05:37.720 --> 01:05:40.520
And it's just a real
lovely, good solid,

01:05:40.520 --> 01:05:44.050
good solid churchgoing
Baltimore family.

01:05:44.050 --> 01:05:47.050
Like they were completely like
that's all about education

01:05:47.050 --> 01:05:49.560
and health, you know, kids--

01:05:49.560 --> 01:05:51.570
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Giving back
to the community for sure.

01:05:51.570 --> 01:05:54.320
And if I could put something there
about Annie, which I've observed

01:05:54.320 --> 01:05:58.480
about many people but Annie would
be prominent who follow the music.

01:05:58.480 --> 01:06:00.420
There are people who
have instruments

01:06:00.420 --> 01:06:02.790
who aren't really musicians
but they have instruments.

01:06:02.790 --> 01:06:04.090
And I'm not naming names.

01:06:04.090 --> 01:06:05.720
No one anywhere in our vicinity,

01:06:05.720 --> 01:06:07.460
but they're out there
and God bless them.

01:06:07.460 --> 01:06:09.780
There are other people who
don't have instruments,

01:06:09.780 --> 01:06:11.890
they're around instruments
but they don't play,

01:06:11.890 --> 01:06:13.800
but they're musicians
through and through.

01:06:13.800 --> 01:06:16.890
And to me Annie is exhibit
A. She's got more music

01:06:16.890 --> 01:06:18.190
in her than a dozen people.

01:06:18.190 --> 01:06:19.490
She doesn't happen
to play an instrument

01:06:19.490 --> 01:06:23.360
but that's just mechanics, but
she's got the music right here.

01:06:23.360 --> 01:06:24.660
How can she not, being around them.

01:06:24.660 --> 01:06:25.960
She knows it.

01:06:25.960 --> 01:06:27.690
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: She was
the one that spotted today here

01:06:27.690 --> 01:06:30.980
that we hadn't-- we didn't have
the concertina, right, among these

01:06:30.980 --> 01:06:32.740
and she's going that--
There's something wrong there.

01:06:32.740 --> 01:06:34.040
We have to have one.

01:06:34.040 --> 01:06:35.340
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: You
mean the sound of it.

01:06:35.340 --> 01:06:36.640
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, so--

01:06:36.640 --> 01:06:37.940
And it was just a matter
of getting another mic.

01:06:37.940 --> 01:06:39.480
But she brought that,
we think, oh, it's fine,

01:06:39.480 --> 01:06:40.780
but she heard it, you know.

01:06:40.780 --> 01:06:42.080
Yeah.

01:06:42.080 --> 01:06:43.380
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: She-- Her
ear is as good as anybody

01:06:43.380 --> 01:06:44.680
who plays the instrument.

01:06:44.680 --> 01:06:48.110
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: She
connects-- she connects people.

01:06:48.110 --> 01:06:49.510
Yeah, it's really good.

01:06:49.510 --> 01:06:53.220
That our little community, our
little Irish music community.

01:06:53.220 --> 01:06:54.560
We call that the Celtic corridor.

01:06:54.560 --> 01:06:58.700
They are on Harford Road, there's a
whole bunch of us that play there.

01:06:58.700 --> 01:07:03.670
And Annie is like-- Well, what
would Annie say about that?

01:07:03.670 --> 01:07:06.040
She is like doesn't--
She thinks, you know--

01:07:06.040 --> 01:07:07.340
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: OK, so if
Annie says it's good, it's good.

01:07:07.340 --> 01:07:08.640
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah, she
has a tremendous listening ear.

01:07:08.640 --> 01:07:10.220
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: You
don't need a second opinion.

01:07:10.220 --> 01:07:12.040
You can take her to the bank.

01:07:12.040 --> 01:07:13.340
That's what I think of Annie.

01:07:13.340 --> 01:07:14.640
I think she's awesome.

01:07:14.640 --> 01:07:16.780
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Except she has
zero interest in money, you know.

01:07:16.780 --> 01:07:18.220
It's not--

01:07:18.220 --> 01:07:21.170
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: It's a
figure of speech, you know, so--

01:07:21.170 --> 01:07:23.780
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So I guess
jumping off from discussing Annie

01:07:23.780 --> 01:07:27.220
and the fact that we have
this concert specifically

01:07:27.220 --> 01:07:29.900
to showcase your children as well

01:07:29.900 --> 01:07:32.770
as your own playing
and we have Sean here.

01:07:32.770 --> 01:07:36.900
So let's talk to Sean for
a minute and ask, you know,

01:07:36.900 --> 01:07:41.730
what elements of your music did
you draw from your dad's tradition

01:07:41.730 --> 01:07:45.120
and what have you done
with it that's different?

01:07:45.120 --> 01:07:49.240
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: Well, I
mean, he was my primary influence

01:07:49.240 --> 01:07:52.190
as you can obviously imagine.

01:07:52.190 --> 01:07:53.870
I was not in a situation

01:07:53.870 --> 01:07:57.160
where I immediately wanted
to play the accordion.

01:07:57.160 --> 01:08:00.850
When I was younger I was kind of--

01:08:00.850 --> 01:08:04.510
which is some trend in my life
that I've come to realize,

01:08:04.510 --> 01:08:06.730
I tend to be a bit of
a late bloomer in terms

01:08:06.730 --> 01:08:08.790
of figuring out what I want.

01:08:08.790 --> 01:08:15.790
And I played piano, I learned
piano from Donna Long before

01:08:15.790 --> 01:08:20.310
and then took some fiddle
lessons from Brian Conway,

01:08:20.310 --> 01:08:22.500
who I just saw this weekend.

01:08:22.500 --> 01:08:28.110 position:56%
Who made a funny joke, he was like--
and he said this, he said he likes

01:08:28.110 --> 01:08:32.190
to joke around on the stage with
you guys, that he's responsible

01:08:32.190 --> 01:08:34.970
for my playing the
accordion because he gave me--

01:08:34.970 --> 01:08:36.270
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz:
He's a fiddle player.

01:08:36.270 --> 01:08:38.830
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: -- he gave
me my very last fiddle lesson.

01:08:38.830 --> 01:08:42.960
And after that-- after the--
after that I started playing--

01:08:42.960 --> 01:08:46.800
I kind of waffled for another
couple months or a year,

01:08:46.800 --> 01:08:48.890
I forgot exactly how long.

01:08:48.890 --> 01:08:51.420
But I started playing the
accordion in the Catskills

01:08:51.420 --> 01:08:54.960
with my cousin Noreen,
Noreen Murphy outside

01:08:54.960 --> 01:08:58.990
of Stack's pub in East Durham.

01:08:58.990 --> 01:09:02.670 position:56%
And actually it was John Redmond who
gave me and taught me my first tune.

01:09:02.670 --> 01:09:03.970
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Yeah.

01:09:03.970 --> 01:09:05.270
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: I
still tell him that.

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:06.570
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz:
Yeah, Wexford man.

01:09:06.570 --> 01:09:07.870
Great, great man.

01:09:07.870 --> 01:09:10.030
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: And from there
just kind of organically happened.

01:09:10.030 --> 01:09:15.140
I was around it and it came easily.

01:09:15.140 --> 01:09:17.440
So-- and then I would
kind of tag along and go

01:09:17.440 --> 01:09:19.640
to the Augusta Weeks
and the Catskill Weeks.

01:09:19.640 --> 01:09:21.820
And there was a good
10-year stretch,

01:09:21.820 --> 01:09:24.720
where I did that every year.

01:09:24.720 --> 01:09:28.770
So, through that I,
you know, I got hooked.

01:09:28.770 --> 01:09:30.130
I made a bunch of friends.

01:09:30.130 --> 01:09:34.720
I started meeting girls
and kind of once you do--

01:09:34.720 --> 01:09:38.110
once you experience that sort of
dynamic, you kind of get roped in.

01:09:38.110 --> 01:09:43.080
And, you know, through that,
obviously, I learned a lot

01:09:43.080 --> 01:09:46.160
of what I-- very wide majority

01:09:46.160 --> 01:09:51.740
of my musical technique
and style from him.

01:09:51.740 --> 01:09:56.850
And in recent years, I've kind
of taken that and kind of gone

01:09:56.850 --> 01:10:01.010
in different directions
with it, experimentally.

01:10:01.010 --> 01:10:04.990
Because one thing that I did when
I was younger I found to be sort

01:10:04.990 --> 01:10:09.350
of intimidating, growing
up in the shadows,

01:10:09.350 --> 01:10:13.910
so to speak of, you
know, all of this.

01:10:13.910 --> 01:10:17.660
And how do I kind of figure
out what I want to do?

01:10:17.660 --> 01:10:19.030
Do I want to copy that?

01:10:19.030 --> 01:10:22.730
Or do I want to do something else?

01:10:22.730 --> 01:10:26.420
And so, I, you know, I'm from
Baltimore and I'm an American

01:10:26.420 --> 01:10:30.110
and around me is a lot
of American music so some

01:10:30.110 --> 01:10:32.400
of the collaborations I've
done in the past few years,

01:10:32.400 --> 01:10:38.560
in addition to my traditional
Irish collaborations with people

01:10:38.560 --> 01:10:44.960
like Sean Gavin from Detroit and
Tony Smith, his daughters which--

01:10:44.960 --> 01:10:47.120
that's a whole story that
we didn't really cover.

01:10:47.120 --> 01:10:48.610
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
There's a hundred.

01:10:48.610 --> 01:10:49.910
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: Yeah.

01:10:49.910 --> 01:10:52.740
That's a tangent I'm trying
not to go down but, you know,

01:10:52.740 --> 01:10:59.230
I've taken what I've learned
in my, you know, lessons

01:10:59.230 --> 01:11:04.730
or whatever you want to call it
from my father and gone, you know,

01:11:04.730 --> 01:11:07.930
collaborations with people
like Christylez Bacon.

01:11:07.930 --> 01:11:10.680
I don't know if people
know him in DC.

01:11:10.680 --> 01:11:14.660
Christylez Bacon is a resident
DC pop artist and I've done a lot

01:11:14.660 --> 01:11:17.230
of stuff with him over
the past few years.

01:11:17.230 --> 01:11:22.820
And playing different kinds of like
go-go and jazz and hip hop music

01:11:22.820 --> 01:11:29.760
and playing more recently into
Appalachian music and Bluegrass

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:31.190
and that sort of stuff, so.

01:11:31.190 --> 01:11:32.830
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Tell them your
band name too for the record.

01:11:32.830 --> 01:11:34.680
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: The past
couple years, I've been playing

01:11:34.680 --> 01:11:38.260
with the group called Charm
City Junction which is the name,

01:11:38.260 --> 01:11:41.540
you know, is getting back
to Baltimore, the Charm City

01:11:41.540 --> 01:11:43.810
and the junction point of our
different music coming together.

01:11:43.810 --> 01:11:46.270
So, it's a collaboration
with Bluegrass

01:11:46.270 --> 01:11:50.370
with a player named Patrick
McAvinue, full time banjo player,

01:11:50.370 --> 01:11:53.220
Brad Kolodner, who's the
son of Ken Kolodner who's

01:11:53.220 --> 01:11:56.200
in Helicon with Chris Norman.

01:11:56.200 --> 01:12:04.310
All that. And jazz
bassist Alex Lacquement.

01:12:04.310 --> 01:12:10.190
So, he's a military brat, he
comes from all over the place.

01:12:10.190 --> 01:12:12.660 position:56%
So, it's kind of taking me all sorts

01:12:12.660 --> 01:12:15.110
of different places
that I, you know.

01:12:15.110 --> 01:12:17.700
And one of the interesting
things about that, for me,

01:12:17.700 --> 01:12:21.930
I remember being a little kid
is going to these festivals.

01:12:21.930 --> 01:12:25.590
And you know, I would say,
"You never know, you never know

01:12:25.590 --> 01:12:27.150
where music is going to take you."

01:12:27.150 --> 01:12:28.450
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Yeah.

01:12:28.450 --> 01:12:30.010
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: And wherever
you go you have a friend.

01:12:30.010 --> 01:12:33.590
So yeah, you know, in the
past between the past 5

01:12:33.590 --> 01:12:36.270
and 10 years I've, you
know, toured in Germany

01:12:36.270 --> 01:12:39.520
with Josh Dukes and quite in Spain.

01:12:39.520 --> 01:12:42.660
All of the country here.

01:12:42.660 --> 01:12:44.370
It's pretty interesting.

01:12:44.370 --> 01:12:45.670
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Great.

01:12:45.670 --> 01:12:48.460
So, you know, one thing you're
talking about these webs

01:12:48.460 --> 01:12:51.480
and it was funny because when you
brought up the Bothy Band Billy

01:12:51.480 --> 01:12:54.260
and were asking "what's
the name of the guy."

01:12:54.260 --> 01:12:57.280
I thought you were referring
to Mícheál Ó Domhnaill,

01:12:57.280 --> 01:12:59.220
because he added in a
lot of the harmonics.

01:12:59.220 --> 01:13:00.520
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
Yeah, all those guys.

01:13:00.520 --> 01:13:01.820
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Although
obviously Donal was--

01:13:01.820 --> 01:13:03.160
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: He could--
But he could pick either one,

01:13:03.160 --> 01:13:05.120
I picked Donal but
it could be Mícheál.

01:13:05.120 --> 01:13:06.420
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And the reason I--

01:13:06.420 --> 01:13:07.720
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
Was it Kevin Burke?

01:13:07.720 --> 01:13:09.020
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

01:13:09.020 --> 01:13:10.320
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

01:13:10.320 --> 01:13:13.400
But I thought of him because,
you know, you weren't in a band

01:13:13.400 --> 01:13:16.750 position:56%
with Mícheál but you were in a band
with someone very closely associated

01:13:16.750 --> 01:13:18.660
with Mícheál early on
with who was Dáithí .

01:13:18.660 --> 01:13:19.960
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: That's right.

01:13:19.960 --> 01:13:22.930
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: And so,
that style of guitar playing.

01:13:22.930 --> 01:13:27.140
Yeah. So talk a little bit about
Trian, just because we didn't get

01:13:27.140 --> 01:13:30.820
to it, and you mentioned
Liz from the stage today?

01:13:30.820 --> 01:13:33.510
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
I remember being in--

01:13:33.510 --> 01:13:37.310
But before I moved down here,
I went to a feis in Manhattan

01:13:37.310 --> 01:13:41.070
and then we thought it was a
really a big time at the feis

01:13:41.070 --> 01:13:45.580
and that's an Irish
dancing competition thing.

01:13:45.580 --> 01:13:52.720
And that there was a few musicians
I actually went to and a couple

01:13:52.720 --> 01:13:55.270
of friends of mine said,
"There's some girl, she's tall,

01:13:55.270 --> 01:14:00.010 position:56%
she's really crazy she and she's
been asking, she wants to meet you."

01:14:00.010 --> 01:14:01.310
I said, "Really?"

01:14:01.310 --> 01:14:02.610
I said, "What's her name?"

01:14:02.610 --> 01:14:03.910 position:56%
They said, "Her name is Liz Caroll."

01:14:03.910 --> 01:14:05.210
I said, "Really?"

01:14:05.210 --> 01:14:07.660
I said, "That sounds great and I
think I'm going to have to look."

01:14:07.660 --> 01:14:10.120
And they say, "Yeah, she's really
tall, she's about six foot tall."

01:14:10.120 --> 01:14:11.420
And she's a basketball.

01:14:11.420 --> 01:14:14.800
She's like a softball player,
she's an athlete, you know.

01:14:14.800 --> 01:14:16.100
I said, "Really?

01:14:16.100 --> 01:14:17.400
That's really something."

01:14:17.400 --> 01:14:18.700
So I was just-- We were
just kind of walking

01:14:18.700 --> 01:14:20.270
around and having a few tune.

01:14:20.270 --> 01:14:24.540
Eugene O'Donnell was there, Michael
Flatley was there playing a tune,

01:14:24.540 --> 01:14:29.300
he sounded very much like a
Seamus Tansey, he plays in Sligo--

01:14:29.300 --> 01:14:32.810
who was the great Sligo flute
player that lives in Chicago now?

01:14:32.810 --> 01:14:34.110
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Kevin Henry.

01:14:34.110 --> 01:14:35.410
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: Kevin Henry.

01:14:35.410 --> 01:14:36.950
He was a student of Kevin Henry
and I was looking for her,

01:14:36.950 --> 01:14:41.880
I thought Mike Flynn was there and
it was this kid, Michael Flatley.

01:14:41.880 --> 01:14:44.610
And the next thing, where
all of the, all these nuts,

01:14:44.610 --> 01:14:46.500
everybody is on the
elevator and you should--

01:14:46.500 --> 01:14:49.970
nobody, you shouldn't have beer
in the hotel because, you know,

01:14:49.970 --> 01:14:51.860
you get in trouble for
having beer walking around.

01:14:51.860 --> 01:14:54.950
You're spilling all over the rugs
and it was stupid and a big mess.

01:14:54.950 --> 01:14:59.110
And the doors open and this girl,
Patty Moriarty, a box player,

01:15:00.900 --> 01:15:06.070
very well educated, but again,
totally crazy, great, great person

01:15:06.070 --> 01:15:08.560 position:56%
and a lovely player for the dancing.

01:15:08.560 --> 01:15:10.870
And the door is open and
she goes, "There he is."

01:15:10.870 --> 01:15:14.490
And this girl, she's
about 6 foot 2, she goes,

01:15:14.490 --> 01:15:17.450
"Is that Bi-- " and
the doors closed.

01:15:17.450 --> 01:15:20.090
So, that was the first time
that I met Liz Carroll.

01:15:20.090 --> 01:15:22.150
I was like, you got
to be kidding me.

01:15:22.150 --> 01:15:27.680
And we-- And so-- And I didn't
see her again that weekend.

01:15:27.680 --> 01:15:30.260
And then, something
was going on here.

01:15:30.260 --> 01:15:32.730
One of those, there was a
while when there was a couple--

01:15:32.730 --> 01:15:39.940 position:56%
There was a fellow, Sean -- what the
hell, it was Sean or Brian, what--

01:15:39.940 --> 01:15:43.720
Brian that's always with
the concertina Copley.

01:15:43.720 --> 01:15:47.910
Sean Copley [assumed spelling] got
himself a little three-year grant

01:15:47.910 --> 01:15:50.130
to have a folk festival.

01:15:50.130 --> 01:15:52.810
And we go, "What are
you going to do?

01:15:52.810 --> 01:15:54.740
Someone's going to give you money."

01:15:54.740 --> 01:15:56.040
You know, he's like, "This is--

01:15:56.040 --> 01:15:58.170
My Uncle Matt would have
love that, you know."

01:15:58.170 --> 01:16:00.190
So, he gets in and he calls
up, he says, "Who do you think,

01:16:00.190 --> 01:16:01.490
who do you think is a good player?

01:16:01.490 --> 01:16:02.790
Who should we get?"

01:16:02.790 --> 01:16:05.050
I said, you know, "Liz Carroll,
you know, she's really good."

01:16:05.050 --> 01:16:09.400
The next thing, she
started being places.

01:16:09.400 --> 01:16:15.760 position:56%
But the real big one, again, was
the 1976, the bicentennial festival.

01:16:15.760 --> 01:16:17.130
There she was.

01:16:17.130 --> 01:16:21.620
And it was like between herself
and Michael, there was kind of,

01:16:21.620 --> 01:16:24.640
you know, the rest of us
were feeling a little rusty,

01:16:24.640 --> 01:16:27.260
a little we-- we kind of have to
start practicing a little bit.

01:16:27.260 --> 01:16:30.220
Liz is like, you know,
I think she's a genius.

01:16:30.220 --> 01:16:36.350
I think she would be pre-eminent
player, period, you know.

01:16:36.350 --> 01:16:38.380
She's just-- She's unbelievable.

01:16:38.380 --> 01:16:40.730
I don't even know how many
solo recordings she have.

01:16:40.730 --> 01:16:44.430
But that should, you know, and
then, you know, when I got married,

01:16:44.430 --> 01:16:45.730
I ended up in Baltimore then.

01:16:45.730 --> 01:16:50.140 position:56%
You know, I didn't want to be coming
down here going crazy all the time

01:16:50.140 --> 01:16:55.820
and trying to figure out, you
know, how to be a man, you know.

01:16:55.820 --> 01:17:02.600
And so, we all kind of
changed what we were doing.

01:17:02.600 --> 01:17:07.900 position:56%
One of the big things that I managed
to do was I just stopped drinking,

01:17:07.900 --> 01:17:12.420
I thought-- I love to drink
but I love to play more.

01:17:12.420 --> 01:17:13.720
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yes.

01:17:13.720 --> 01:17:15.020
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: So,
I figure, OK, I'll just--

01:17:15.020 --> 01:17:16.320
I think I'll just be a player.

01:17:16.320 --> 01:17:18.200
So, I did my best in AA,
you know, things are sort

01:17:18.200 --> 01:17:21.830
of like calming down, realizing
what it is, I asked where I was

01:17:21.830 --> 01:17:23.880
and all these kind of stuff.

01:17:23.880 --> 01:17:29.950
And Liz was nesting in Chicago.

01:17:29.950 --> 01:17:32.990
She had a couple-- She
had a son and a daughter,

01:17:32.990 --> 01:17:34.790
great kids, really lovely.

01:17:34.790 --> 01:17:37.140
And her husband is terrific.

01:17:37.140 --> 01:17:41.480
And he was a carpenter and he would
play blues, Charles, Charles Lacey.

01:17:41.480 --> 01:17:42.780
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Great
blues harp player?

01:17:42.780 --> 01:17:44.080
You know, harmonica.

01:17:44.080 --> 01:17:45.730
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: And then
she just gave me a call one day

01:17:45.730 --> 01:17:49.950
and she says, "Billy, why
don't we have a group?"

01:17:49.950 --> 01:17:52.900
And I said, "Well, OK.

01:17:52.900 --> 01:17:54.200
Works for me."

01:17:54.200 --> 01:17:56.390
I had a little job, it was
a little tough getting away,

01:17:56.390 --> 01:18:00.650
but as I was starting to get
little bits of vacation time

01:18:00.650 --> 01:18:02.810
and maybe could go on
the weekends and we go--

01:18:02.810 --> 01:18:04.370
and really go on the
way again as we could.

01:18:04.370 --> 01:18:10.540
And Dáithí had-- Dáithí had come
out with a box player from Offaly,

01:18:10.540 --> 01:18:12.200
again named Paddy O'Brien,
named, you know,

01:18:12.200 --> 01:18:15.380 position:56%
the same as the great Paddy O'Brien.

01:18:15.380 --> 01:18:18.960
And-- But James Kelly
was the fiddle player.

01:18:18.960 --> 01:18:21.300
So, it was the three
of them that came out.

01:18:21.300 --> 01:18:25.040
And the first time I heard
them was at the Dubliner.

01:18:25.040 --> 01:18:28.380
You know-- I could--
I was like, my Lord,

01:18:28.380 --> 01:18:30.980
their repertoire was really great.

01:18:30.980 --> 01:18:35.940
Paddy was the box player
in the Castle Ceili band.

01:18:35.940 --> 01:18:40.830
He took the James Keane seat
when James immigrated to America.

01:18:40.830 --> 01:18:45.760
James Keane is the brother of
Sean Keane from the Chieftains.

01:18:45.760 --> 01:18:48.440
So, Paddy came out
and I think it was--

01:18:48.440 --> 01:18:50.990
I got the feeling that it might
have been James Kelly's idea.

01:18:50.990 --> 01:18:54.000
He'd been out the year
before on a Ceoltas tour

01:18:54.000 --> 01:18:56.340
and he came in to Dubliner.

01:18:56.340 --> 01:18:59.190
And he saw what was
going on over here.

01:18:59.190 --> 01:19:00.850
It was pandemonium.

01:19:00.850 --> 01:19:08.570
It was mobs of people-- it paid
a weekly cash, you know, we've--

01:19:08.570 --> 01:19:12.770 position:56%
some of us paid taxes, I think, you
know, everybody was all pretty good.

01:19:12.770 --> 01:19:15.090
And he's like, "Maybe
I'll try this."

01:19:15.090 --> 01:19:20.030
And his father, John Kelly
would be one of the pillars

01:19:20.030 --> 01:19:24.180
of Irish traditional music,
the great West Clare fiddler.

01:19:24.180 --> 01:19:30.800 position:56%
He was one of those founding
teachers for the Willie Clancy Week.

01:19:30.800 --> 01:19:33.170
I think, I'm pretty sure
John was still alive

01:19:33.170 --> 01:19:35.490
on the Willie Clancy Week start up.

01:19:35.490 --> 01:19:38.620
So, James is like-- James is
living down in Florida now.

01:19:38.620 --> 01:19:41.860 position:56%
And I just learned so much from him.

01:19:41.860 --> 01:19:45.750
He's like-- He would be
defined as a fiddle--

01:19:45.750 --> 01:19:47.300
the fiddle player's fiddler.

01:19:47.300 --> 01:19:50.080
You know, a fiddler
player's fiddler.

01:19:50.080 --> 01:19:51.380
That's James.

01:19:51.380 --> 01:19:54.200
And he asked Dáithí Sproule.

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:56.620
And Dáithí had been--
he was living in--

01:19:56.620 --> 01:20:00.150
I guess, he was living in
Dublin and he was going to--

01:20:00.150 --> 01:20:03.120
he'd finished college and he was,
I guess, was a little bit angry.

01:20:03.120 --> 01:20:09.100
He was from Derry and all his
stuff was really interesting.

01:20:09.100 --> 01:20:11.470
When he gets to-- It's
just now that he's starting

01:20:11.470 --> 01:20:12.770
to talk about it, you know.

01:20:12.770 --> 01:20:17.800
All these idiotic, awful
stuff, this murderous stuff

01:20:17.800 --> 01:20:19.460
with the British army
there in Derry.

01:20:19.460 --> 01:20:20.980
And so, he was there.

01:20:20.980 --> 01:20:27.000 position:56%
He saw some of this, but he was--
he's a totally not a violent person.

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:31.830
But he absolutely fell-- He fell
in love with this DADGAD tuning.

01:20:31.830 --> 01:20:34.390
And I never-- I'm not sure,

01:20:34.390 --> 01:20:37.370
but I think Arty McGlynn
might have been the first

01:20:37.370 --> 01:20:40.370
of the great guitar accompanists.

01:20:40.370 --> 01:20:43.580
He was the first really, really,
really great guitar player.

01:20:43.580 --> 01:20:49.920
Andy O'Brien knew his music inside
out and he was able to interpret it

01:20:49.920 --> 01:20:52.850
with the skill that he had acquired
from watching other players.

01:20:52.850 --> 01:20:54.900
I don't know if I'm
saying that right,

01:20:54.900 --> 01:21:01.210
but Arty was an unbelievably
great guitar player.

01:21:01.210 --> 01:21:02.510
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

01:21:02.510 --> 01:21:04.860
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: With
a natural love and respect

01:21:04.860 --> 01:21:07.850
for Irish traditional music.

01:21:07.850 --> 01:21:09.350
And what's his wife--

01:21:09.350 --> 01:21:10.760
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Well,
ex-wife Nollaig Casey

01:21:10.760 --> 01:21:12.060
and they still work together.

01:21:12.060 --> 01:21:13.360
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
They're still great.

01:21:13.360 --> 01:21:14.660
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick:

01:21:14.660 --> 01:21:15.960
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
Brilliant, brilliant,

01:21:15.960 --> 01:21:17.260
brilliant player, brilliant
accompanist.

01:21:17.260 --> 01:21:18.560
So, these would have
been the people--

01:21:18.560 --> 01:21:20.090
kind of like the people that
Dáithí would have been listened to.

01:21:20.090 --> 01:21:23.020 position:56%
So the three of them came out and
we heard them there in the Dubliner.

01:21:23.020 --> 01:21:25.450
And they went on to
make two records.

01:21:25.450 --> 01:21:29.790
And Liz was gotten so-- the
Irish tradition, we were kind--

01:21:29.790 --> 01:21:31.540
we would kind of had our time.

01:21:31.540 --> 01:21:35.960
We were-- We weren't
a very good bar band.

01:21:35.960 --> 01:21:40.000
We-- everything worked really,

01:21:40.000 --> 01:21:41.610
really well for us
there in the Dubliner.

01:21:41.610 --> 01:21:47.240 position:56%
We were very, very lucky that the
audience that we had on Capitol Hill

01:21:47.240 --> 01:21:52.050
at the time was as
attuned as they were.

01:21:52.050 --> 01:21:57.600 position:56%
It was just a magnificent thing that
happened, again, Myron with WGTB

01:21:57.600 --> 01:22:00.590
and then National Council
for the Traditional Arts.

01:22:00.590 --> 01:22:02.180 position:56%
We had tremendous support, you know.

01:22:02.180 --> 01:22:05.890
And then, all of a
sudden, we didn't.

01:22:05.890 --> 01:22:08.410
And it was-- We couldn't
really take it.

01:22:08.410 --> 01:22:11.230
We wanted a concert, we
definitely were not travelers.

01:22:11.230 --> 01:22:14.280
We were-- We did not have that.

01:22:14.280 --> 01:22:15.770
We didn't have that.

01:22:15.770 --> 01:22:18.660
And so-- And Liz was
the one-- that Liz--

01:22:18.660 --> 01:22:21.590
when the kids got a little
bigger and then she just said,

01:22:21.590 --> 01:22:22.890
"Why don't we have a group?

01:22:22.890 --> 01:22:24.190
We'll start a group?"

01:22:24.190 --> 01:22:25.490
And we did.

01:22:25.490 --> 01:22:29.150
And we did gigs in the Midwest
while we're figuring out how to--

01:22:29.150 --> 01:22:31.670
I'd figured out how
to accompany Andy.

01:22:31.670 --> 01:22:35.920
Andy liked all these
flat keys, you know.

01:22:35.920 --> 01:22:37.720
The great singers will
sing in the key

01:22:37.720 --> 01:22:39.910 position:56%
that suits the song suits the voice.

01:22:39.910 --> 01:22:47.490
So, we are able to come up with
some really nice settings of tunes

01:22:47.490 --> 01:22:52.150
and we-- Liz and I were
both composing tunes.

01:22:52.150 --> 01:22:55.820
Liz still is, Liz is a
really prolific composer.

01:22:55.820 --> 01:22:57.520
So, yeah, so we made
the two records.

01:22:57.520 --> 01:22:58.940
And it was really good.

01:22:58.940 --> 01:23:01.510
We got quite a couple
of-- the national fest--

01:23:01.510 --> 01:23:05.650
folk festival and we
played in Ireland.

01:23:05.650 --> 01:23:07.370
We played at the Ennis
trad festival.

01:23:07.370 --> 01:23:10.060
We got to do some really
interesting things.

01:23:10.060 --> 01:23:14.020
I just-- I was just talking with
Dáithí and just played a couple

01:23:14.020 --> 01:23:17.050
of gigs with Joanie Madden
with the Pride of New York,

01:23:17.050 --> 01:23:23.110
which is our little-- my
little band with Joanie Madden

01:23:23.110 --> 01:23:27.130
and Brandon Dolan and Brian Conway.

01:23:27.130 --> 01:23:28.450
And Dáithí joined us.

01:23:28.450 --> 01:23:30.280
It's such a great band.

01:23:30.280 --> 01:23:36.760
And he had a really
stellar career with Altan.

01:23:36.760 --> 01:23:41.550
So, he really knows he fits
right into this lovely ensemble.

01:23:41.550 --> 01:23:42.850
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: Yeah.

01:23:42.850 --> 01:23:44.800
And that Pride of New York just,
again, shows that connection

01:23:44.800 --> 01:23:48.990
to the previous generation
because you think of Brian Conway,

01:23:48.990 --> 01:23:52.700
learning from Andy McGann and
you learning from Sean McGlynn

01:23:52.700 --> 01:23:55.500
and Joanie learning from
her father, Joe Madden,

01:23:55.500 --> 01:23:57.130
just such great connections
there and--

01:23:57.130 --> 01:23:58.430
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: I
guess the incredible thing

01:23:58.430 --> 01:23:59.880
about the record was we made--

01:23:59.880 --> 01:24:04.290
we recorded it in a
weekend in Joanie's house.

01:24:04.290 --> 01:24:07.040
And so, the idea was, "Well,
what should we play first?"

01:24:07.040 --> 01:24:10.230
And we all thought (Sings tune).

01:24:10.230 --> 01:24:11.530
We all thought of this.

01:24:11.530 --> 01:24:14.940
They call it "The Dublin Reel"
now with Larry Redican, right.

01:24:14.940 --> 01:24:16.240
And so, when we were--

01:24:16.240 --> 01:24:17.540
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Galway Reel.

01:24:17.540 --> 01:24:18.840
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
The Galway Reel.

01:24:18.840 --> 01:24:20.140
What did I say?

01:24:20.140 --> 01:24:21.440
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Dublin.

01:24:21.440 --> 01:24:22.740
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey: The Dublin.

01:24:22.740 --> 01:24:24.040
So, here, you know, he's-- So,
we started-- No, it's fine.

01:24:24.040 --> 01:24:26.940
So we started playing the tune and
then we go, boy, Larry wouldn't--

01:24:26.940 --> 01:24:28.310
oh, Larry was just terrific.

01:24:28.310 --> 01:24:29.720
And we'd sit there
and talk about it.

01:24:29.720 --> 01:24:31.490
Well, what would be good with that?

01:24:31.490 --> 01:24:32.790
Well, you know.

01:24:32.790 --> 01:24:34.590
Why don't we put that
one in the tunes?

01:24:34.590 --> 01:24:38.460
That tune that James Keane...oh,
yeah, those are really good.

01:24:38.460 --> 01:24:43.700
OK. And we never really
rehearsed the record, you know.

01:24:43.700 --> 01:24:48.370
It's just-- We put them together
and it's great fun with the--

01:24:48.370 --> 01:24:52.080
I got the chance where I butt
heads there with Brendan,

01:24:52.080 --> 01:24:54.620
you know, or how should, you know.

01:24:54.620 --> 01:24:57.950
How do you see this and what do
you think we could, you know,

01:24:57.950 --> 01:25:00.890
lilting little chord ideas he had.

01:25:00.890 --> 01:25:04.200
And he's so fast he never--
he never had to punch.

01:25:04.200 --> 01:25:07.160
He never had to edit anything,

01:25:07.160 --> 01:25:09.470
anything that Brendan
Dolan did on that record.

01:25:09.470 --> 01:25:11.190
"How do you like that Brendan?"

01:25:11.190 --> 01:25:13.150
"Oh, it's fine."

01:25:13.150 --> 01:25:15.420
&gt;&gt; Steve Winick: So, I'm afraid
we're running low on time.

01:25:15.420 --> 01:25:20.030
So, I would like to just
ask Sean and Myron quickly

01:25:20.030 --> 01:25:24.640 position:56%
to give a little comment about Billy
and his playing and maybe his--

01:25:24.640 --> 01:25:27.950
the award that he's going to
be picking up in a little bit.

01:25:27.950 --> 01:25:31.010
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: Can I go first
because I think it will be right

01:25:31.010 --> 01:25:33.810
to end with Sean being Billy's son,
that would be very valedictory.

01:25:33.810 --> 01:25:35.240
Is that OK Sean?

01:25:35.240 --> 01:25:36.540
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: Gives me
time to think some thoughts.

01:25:36.540 --> 01:25:38.650
&gt;&gt; Myron Bretholz: You
differ the age here.

01:25:38.650 --> 01:25:41.940
I do believe McComiskey
coming on 40 years.

01:25:41.940 --> 01:25:44.950
I met him not long after he
started playing at Dubliner.

01:25:44.950 --> 01:25:51.740
And he is a massive,
massive musical influence

01:25:51.740 --> 01:25:55.110
on me playing the humble
lowly Irish drum.

01:25:55.110 --> 01:25:58.560
But, you need an education
to play anything

01:25:58.560 --> 01:26:01.990
and I had the best teacher alive
and that's Billy McComiskey.

01:26:01.990 --> 01:26:05.160
And I also feel-- I've
said it anyone who--

01:26:05.160 --> 01:26:06.480
anyone who's ever asked, they go,

01:26:06.480 --> 01:26:08.220
"What's it like playing
with Billy McComiskey?"

01:26:08.220 --> 01:26:09.520
I always said.

01:26:09.520 --> 01:26:10.820
I'll tell you what it's like.

01:26:10.820 --> 01:26:13.580
I'd rather get on the stage with
Billy unrehearsed and unprepared

01:26:13.580 --> 01:26:15.980
than with anyone else
with 10 rehearsals.

01:26:15.980 --> 01:26:18.070 position:56%
That's how sure I feel around Billy.

01:26:18.070 --> 01:26:20.670
It just going to be right.

01:26:20.670 --> 01:26:23.580
Not that we don't rehearse, not
that we don't keep our game up,

01:26:23.580 --> 01:26:27.940 position:56%
but I know that if he says something
it's going to lay down just right.

01:26:27.940 --> 01:26:31.630 position:56%
And it's going to be-- it's going to
have integrity, it's going to last,

01:26:31.630 --> 01:26:37.260
it's going to be musically viable
and it might even be some fun.

01:26:37.260 --> 01:26:40.550
Billy is-- I have two wonderful
sisters, I didn't happen to grow

01:26:40.550 --> 01:26:43.740
up with a brother, but I
consider Billy a brother.

01:26:43.740 --> 01:26:46.520
So, that's me and Billy McComiskey.

01:26:46.520 --> 01:26:48.580
I differ to Sean now.

01:26:48.580 --> 01:26:50.990
&gt;&gt; Billy McComiskey:
On the spot now.

01:26:50.990 --> 01:26:54.560
&gt;&gt; Sean McComiskey: Well, I can go
down the road of being meaningful

01:26:54.560 --> 01:26:58.460
and profound, but I think
probably just the simplest thing

01:26:58.460 --> 01:27:06.320
that I can say about my father
is thank you for teaching me

01:27:06.320 --> 01:27:10.580
and my brothers and my
cousins all the good things

01:27:10.580 --> 01:27:12.100
that you taught us about music.

01:27:12.100 --> 01:27:15.630
And the value-- when I
was listening to you talk

01:27:15.630 --> 01:27:16.950
about Sean McGlynn it was--

01:27:16.950 --> 01:27:19.330
I was kind of reminded of some of
the things that you do in terms

01:27:19.330 --> 01:27:23.800
of like never taking money for
teaching lessons or, you know,

01:27:23.800 --> 01:27:25.980
it's all about passing it on.

01:27:25.980 --> 01:27:30.180
It's not about, you know,
anything more than that.

01:27:30.180 --> 01:27:32.420
It's about keeping it
going and sharing it

01:27:32.420 --> 01:27:35.940
because that's the
most important thing

01:27:35.940 --> 01:27:37.400
and being open-minded about it.

01:27:37.400 --> 01:27:39.630
So, thank you.

01:27:39.630 --> 01:27:40.930
Congratulations.

01:27:40.930 --> 01:27:42.230
